And you guys have co-authored a few books together, and I want to talk about those.

04:14.780 --> 04:20.040
Because you've independently offered, you know, a spy in Moscow station.

04:21.240 --> 04:25.100
And you guys have just an incredible background, both individually and together.

04:25.300 --> 04:27.300
So it's an honor to be with you today.

04:27.840 --> 04:28.820
That's a great honor to be here.

04:29.460 --> 04:29.640
Yeah.

04:29.780 --> 04:31.140
Thank you so much for having us.

04:31.340 --> 04:34.860
I wanted to talk about your book, The New Science of UFOs,

04:34.900 --> 04:40.400
because I think it's a really great kind of survey-level overview of all of the possibilities.

04:40.400 --> 04:45.380
I think often in this space, there's a lot of kind of mushy-brained thinking.

04:45.760 --> 04:50.220
And, you know, just almost people are over-indexed on intuition.

04:50.680 --> 05:02.280
And you really kind of lay out all of the possibilities from spoofing techniques to man-made craft to, you know, genuine non-human intelligence.

05:02.480 --> 05:05.260
And then you even get into frameworks for thinking about the non-human intelligence.

05:05.680 --> 05:08.500
So, yeah, why don't we start there?

05:08.500 --> 05:12.500
What are the possibilities kind of high-level when it comes to UFOs?

05:13.400 --> 05:17.580
Well, I'll start, and then you can fill in where I miss things.

05:17.800 --> 05:19.680
First of all, a little context for the book.

05:19.960 --> 05:29.820
I spent years at the CIA after leaving NSA and ODNI, where I was basically the CTO of the U.S. intelligence community, the whole thing.

05:29.820 --> 05:40.720
And I was an analyst for a particular target and was trained in analytic tradecraft, which is basically the scientific method.

05:40.860 --> 05:43.880
And we call it the method of competing hypothesis.

05:44.280 --> 05:51.580
When we see a phenomena or an event, we say, what are all the different hypotheses for what could be driving this?

05:51.580 --> 05:56.880
And then we go and we look for evidence that would support or contradict each of those.

05:57.400 --> 06:08.980
And at the end, we weigh it and come out with an assessment with the probability of what we think is the most likely of all of those with some confidence.

06:08.980 --> 06:20.380
And so, for example, in Iran, you have the Iran group at the different agencies doing that now saying, OK, Iranians have a nuclear program.

06:21.160 --> 06:27.200
What is our best guess and at what probability about where they are in that program and what their intent is?

06:28.060 --> 06:29.000
Right. So that's an example.

06:29.140 --> 06:32.760
So with the UFOs, UAPs, we did the same.

06:32.760 --> 06:35.300
We said, OK, here are the reporting.

06:36.420 --> 06:38.460
What are all the different things that could be?

06:38.580 --> 06:39.600
And now let's examine them.

06:39.660 --> 06:46.960
So we have a matrix in there, which is a little bit geeky in that we present all of them that we surfaced.

06:47.160 --> 06:49.260
And then we evaluate the plus or minus.

06:49.380 --> 06:50.960
And at the end, we come up with a conclusion.

06:51.600 --> 06:54.900
So we start with the observer themselves.

06:55.740 --> 07:02.480
When you look at a phenomena, you have to look at what's reporting it and how accurate and bias is the thing.

07:02.480 --> 07:03.400
That's reporting it.

07:04.220 --> 07:12.620
So the human instrument, as a neuroscientist and as a physician, we can both tell you the human instrument is highly flawed.

07:13.460 --> 07:14.020
Right.

07:14.780 --> 07:24.020
And so we look at things like optical illusions, emotional bias that make you see what you want to see, that make you see what you expect to see.

07:24.120 --> 07:28.920
We get into how your brain is wired to cut corners.

07:28.920 --> 07:33.620
And so we explore optical illusions or other kind of illusions.

07:34.100 --> 07:46.080
We explore atmospheric effects, some of which are just not only being discovered, like sprites at southern latitudes, things really weird, ball lightning, things like that.

07:46.080 --> 08:02.540
We explore the possibility that it's a human origin, highly classified and super high tech.

08:02.540 --> 08:13.380
We explore the possibility that it's of non-human, but of earthly origin.

08:14.460 --> 08:17.320
I mean, we always assume if it's from Earth that it has to be human.

08:17.480 --> 08:21.140
Well, what we look at is the old Sherlock Holmes thing.

08:21.340 --> 08:22.560
What isn't impossible?

08:22.560 --> 08:34.020
And we'll get into this more, but at CIA, we used to have a saying, an analyst that says, do not look for your keys under the lamppost.

08:35.980 --> 08:36.460
Right.

08:36.640 --> 08:38.920
Don't look only where you can see.

08:39.680 --> 08:47.820
So if you're not seeing something, it's probably because you don't know where else to look.

08:47.820 --> 08:54.740
So one thing we used to do is say, what do we know or think we know?

08:54.880 --> 08:56.640
What can we see and not see?

08:56.980 --> 09:02.520
And if we're not finding the answer, it must be the opposite of what we can see.

09:03.360 --> 09:04.900
It's in the negative space.

09:05.740 --> 09:06.220
Right.

09:06.420 --> 09:14.660
So I was once involved in the hunt for a very senior Islamic terrorist whose name I will not mention.

09:14.660 --> 09:20.840
And I was employed by CIA when I was at NSA, and I went to them and I said, you haven't found this guy.

09:21.000 --> 09:23.800
Where do you expect him to be and where do you not expect him?

09:24.020 --> 09:27.300
Where do you want him to be and where do you not want him to be?

09:28.080 --> 09:35.500
And I said, look for him where you least expect and least want him to be, because that's where he's going to be by definition.

09:35.500 --> 09:50.780
Well, my mind is now going to like dark matter or concepts like dark chemistry, parts of the universe that are honestly the majority of the universe, which isn't visible and doesn't seem to interact with light.

09:51.600 --> 09:54.700
And so I don't know if you guys have considered that as a possibility.

09:54.700 --> 10:05.060
Yeah, we're talking also in the book about exo-psychology, which we kind of imagine what would that be, an extraterrestrial, what would that be?

10:05.300 --> 10:09.780
So it could be made of dark matter and feeding on dark energy.

10:10.180 --> 10:16.800
It could be, and we said that it could be anything that we could not think about.

10:16.800 --> 10:19.020
So what are we not thinking about?

10:19.160 --> 10:20.680
What could we not predict?

10:21.180 --> 10:36.300
So we could not predict that they might not derive from animal forms, that they might not derive from plants, that they don't require food or water to survive, maybe.

10:36.780 --> 10:41.500
That maybe they are immortal, that maybe they don't sexually reproduce.

10:41.760 --> 10:44.760
We imagine that they sexually reproduce, maybe not.

10:44.760 --> 10:48.580
Maybe they have no written or spoken language.

10:48.940 --> 10:51.760
Maybe they don't emotionally bond with others.

10:51.920 --> 10:54.160
Maybe they are not a social species.

10:55.200 --> 10:56.680
Maybe they are not curious.

10:57.200 --> 10:58.820
We think they are aggressive.

10:59.000 --> 11:00.140
Maybe they are not aggressive.

11:00.760 --> 11:04.540
What if they have all the resources they can ever need?

11:05.160 --> 11:13.440
What if there are a collection of single cells that origin, develop and live in space and not on the planet?

11:13.440 --> 11:17.080
Maybe we are just surrounded in space, but we don't see them.

11:18.200 --> 11:22.720
And what if they use a type of propulsion that is unknown to us?

11:23.720 --> 11:32.440
We think about every possible ways of moving, but I am sure there are ways that we have no idea exist.

11:33.340 --> 11:34.340
And what are they?

11:34.340 --> 11:40.840
What if they don't derive directly from biology and they are hyper-advanced digital AIs?

11:41.200 --> 11:56.720
I mean, we're trying to think about all the elements that are completely out of the box, that nobody could think about, that nobody can even imagine, that our brain could not even compute.

11:56.720 --> 12:03.180
And then you have to think, you know, we discovered bacteria as late as the 19th century.

12:03.840 --> 12:08.620
And Occam's razor is it's not zero or one thing.

12:08.920 --> 12:11.600
It's, you know, zero or a whole host.

12:11.700 --> 12:15.520
We're swimming in life that might be more advanced than us.

12:16.240 --> 12:16.920
You never know it.

12:17.000 --> 12:17.980
You never know it.

12:17.980 --> 12:30.000
Yeah, the way I think of it is we've all seen those cartoons where the coyote goes through a door and you see the silhouette, you know, where he went through the door.

12:30.380 --> 12:33.320
And so you see where he went through and that's the positive space.

12:33.440 --> 12:35.060
The negative space is the door.

12:35.060 --> 12:42.280
We tend to always focus on the positive space, which in human terms is, in the intelligence world, we call this mirroring.

12:43.040 --> 12:46.060
We look at a target and say, they must be like us.

12:46.240 --> 12:49.400
Therefore, if they're doing X, it's for motivation Y.

12:50.000 --> 12:53.940
So what Dr. Gilbert just said is we did the opposite of that.

12:54.020 --> 13:00.380
We said, let's take everything that humans are and assume that extraterrestrials are none of those.

13:00.380 --> 13:08.620
They're the opposite because we would never think to look there and we never think to understand the motivation.

13:08.840 --> 13:12.320
So, for example, let's take the Tic Tacs.

13:13.000 --> 13:22.280
Suppose the Tic Tacs are driven by an extraterrestrial species that are unlike us in every possible way in the way she just described.

13:23.400 --> 13:25.660
How then would you explain what they're doing?

13:26.000 --> 13:28.320
You wouldn't explain it with human motivations.

13:28.560 --> 13:28.640
No.

13:28.640 --> 13:31.340
You'd explain it with anti-motivations.

13:31.580 --> 13:34.040
And when you do that, it's freeing.

13:34.500 --> 13:37.440
It's kind of like in that movie, Pirates of the Caribbean.

13:38.480 --> 13:45.020
Someone says to Captain Barbosa when they're looking for Captain Jack and they say, Captain, we're lost.

13:45.280 --> 13:49.040
And he goes, I, you have to get lost to find something that can't be found.

13:50.440 --> 13:51.560
And that's deep.

13:52.000 --> 13:53.100
That is really deep.

13:53.100 --> 13:59.380
And that's why, like I say, in the intelligence world, when we're doing our job right, we understand our own limitations.

13:59.380 --> 14:08.220
And one very productive place to look is where we know we're blind and then to purposely try to look there.

14:08.220 --> 14:09.780
Oh, that's so fascinating.

14:09.920 --> 14:15.600
Something I think about a lot with this topic is we think about mining resources.

14:15.840 --> 14:19.960
You know, we have this whole conflict with China around rare earth refinement, for example.

14:20.640 --> 14:27.540
What if their resources, like I think about what's most interesting about human beings, and it's probably not the material world that we're in.

14:27.540 --> 14:28.960
Maybe it's our consciousness.

14:29.680 --> 14:45.060
And so, is there something around our consciousness or even our emotions or our thoughts that are more interesting to these beings than just, you know, they're here for gold or copper or whatever because they're, you know, maybe their atmosphere is burning up.

