But none of those productively explain why it's playing Vivaldi's Four Seasons.

17:35.120 --> 17:37.480
You need to know the frequency it's tapping into.

17:37.480 --> 17:58.140
Yeah. So I'm not saying I'm a fan of noetics, but what I'm saying is that it's so interesting that these ideas show up throughout human history in terms of, like, if you look at the Vedic scriptures and the Hindu and the whole notion of transcendentalism, like, the deity, whatever it is, exists everywhere in all things simultaneously.

17:58.140 --> 18:09.360
And that led to transcendentalism, and you could look at Jung, who believed in the collective unconscious, as an example of the human instantiation of that.

18:09.700 --> 18:16.820
So it is interesting when you see these ideas, and I'd just like to make a comment and then turn it over to Dr. Gilbert.

18:16.820 --> 18:33.340
If you look at our language, we say things like, in our heart, I believe. In my gut, I believe. Right? Or I have this feeling. Those were metaphorical when we thought they were metaphorical.

18:33.340 --> 18:43.740
What we now know is they may not be metaphorical, that we have more neurons in our gut than the cerebral cortex of a monkey, and they're pretty damn smart.

18:43.740 --> 18:55.240
We have a huge number of neurons in our heart. And now we know that cells themselves can have perception and learning, and we have gut bacteria, which are this whole other hyper-complex organism.

18:55.640 --> 19:10.740
And so I think this is the subject of the listening cure, where Dr. Gilbert has come up with this idea of listen to your body, because all of these different entities that we call our body actually are not metaphorical.

19:10.740 --> 19:36.460
Yeah. So the listening cure is one of our books that talks about how our body has a mind of its own, how each organ has a mind of its own, how each cell in the liver, each cell in the gut can have a mind of its own, and a purpose, and maybe feelings, and connection to the brain, and vice versa.

19:36.460 --> 19:57.700
But there are so many things that we think we know. So how is it that we can believe we know everything about space, about the planets, when even in the body, in our own body that we've studied so much, there are things we're discovering that we had no idea existed.

19:57.700 --> 20:14.960
I'm going to give you an example. Like Stanford University researcher did a survey of DNA fragments circulating in the blood, and it suggests that microbes living within us are vastly more diverse than previously thought.

20:14.960 --> 20:38.880
In fact, in fact, 99% of our DNA has never been seen before. And then there's an entirely new class of life that has been found in the human digestive system called obelisks. And there are obelisks, microscopic rods made of RNA that we had no idea existed, and we have no idea what they do.

20:38.880 --> 20:58.060
So, and also in the brain. In the brain, I mean, we think you talk about the Broca area, the Wernicke area. We don't think they're isolated. We think they're working in conjunction of a multitude of other kinds of cells that are necessary for their function.

20:58.060 --> 21:16.060
But we don't know exactly which ones, and we're studying this now. We think that everything is related. Every single item is related to other items in ways that we cannot comprehend yet. And that's the relationship.

21:16.060 --> 21:24.540
And everything in the universe might be, that's my assumption, that's my belief, that everything in the universe is probably also related, interconnected.

21:26.940 --> 21:44.120
And there's so much we don't know. And it is so fascinating to imagine and to discover what we don't know. We probably know maybe 1% of what exists in the world. We think we know so much, but we know so little. And discovering everything is like, oh, it's wonderful.

21:44.120 --> 21:52.340
Even in the human body, it's wonderful. But outside Earth, oh my God, so much.

21:52.460 --> 22:01.560
Yeah. So, I want to circle back to your original question of which hypotheses did we surface in the new science of UFO? Because we didn't finish going into them.

22:01.560 --> 22:16.740
We talk about erasing the difference between space and time, because Einstein didn't think of them as separate. Time is just another dimension, as valid as up, down, left, right, and so forth.

22:16.740 --> 22:22.660
And it's interesting, in all of his field equations, time does not have to move in one direction.

22:23.580 --> 22:31.320
The laws of thermodynamics say it does, but there is no physical equation that says it has to.

22:31.320 --> 22:43.560
And we have some really weird laboratory phenomena and theoretical phenomena that suggest that time, for example, there's this experiment called the quantum eraser.

22:43.920 --> 22:52.980
It's a famous three-slit experiment where you can do something in the present that influences which way a particle or wave behaved in the past.

22:52.980 --> 23:09.680
And then you have the whole business of non-locality, which has something in one part of the universe instantly, or nearly instantly, we now know there's a speed to it, but it's faster than the speed of light, affects something on the other side.

23:09.680 --> 23:25.100
And then we have the whole area of quantum neuroscience, where is entanglement between quantum states in one person's brain or one part of the brain entangled in others in ways that affect or influence, you know?

23:25.400 --> 23:28.400
So what we do is, let's take time.

23:29.760 --> 23:36.120
Everyone assumes that if they're non-humans coming in UFOs, that it must be from outside Earth.

23:36.540 --> 23:39.120
And that may be true, but what if it weren't true?

23:39.680 --> 23:49.780
Let's start with that fork and say, what happens if these things that we're seeing are from Earth, but either from the past, present, or future?

23:50.280 --> 23:53.740
You say, well, time travel backwards is impossible.

23:54.280 --> 23:59.840
Well, in our current framework, most physicists would say that.

23:59.840 --> 24:09.360
And yet, there are these weird phenomena that we talk about in the book, like frame dragging, where if you have a black hole that's spinning really fast, a Schwarzschild black hole.

24:09.680 --> 24:10.660
It's spinning really fast.

24:11.260 --> 24:12.920
The black hole itself isn't just spinning.

24:13.100 --> 24:16.820
It's spinning space-time with it, right?

24:16.960 --> 24:27.140
And so if you were orbiting outside the event horizon of a spinning black hole, there is this thing called the closed time-like curve,

24:27.360 --> 24:31.340
where when you started the orbit and you finished it, you'd end up at the same place in time.

24:32.000 --> 24:34.940
So if you end up where you started, you went back in time.

24:35.840 --> 24:40.420
The math says that is theoretically not impossible, and there's a distinction.

24:41.200 --> 24:48.020
And so you're going to hear this throughout our discussion of what we like to explore is the not impossible,

24:48.340 --> 24:50.660
because we think that's where the answers are.

24:50.660 --> 25:01.660
So to get back to this time thing, one of the things we explore is the possibility that there was some advanced civilization on Earth

25:01.660 --> 25:11.660
many hundreds of millions of years ago, whose evidence has been covered up by the relentless reshaping of the surface of the planet

25:11.660 --> 25:19.980
with tectonic and so forth, various environmental things that happened that we wouldn't necessarily see evidence of it.

25:20.660 --> 25:21.660
And they—

25:21.660 --> 25:22.780
You'd likely not, almost.

25:23.580 --> 25:30.740
Unlikely, given—depending on where it was and so forth, the Earth's crust has folded over on itself and got pushed under and subducted and blah, blah, blah.

25:31.040 --> 25:40.000
And so what if there were an ancient species that discovered near-luminal travel, speed of light, or even faster,

25:40.120 --> 25:46.100
and we can get into that later, you know, what are the possibilities for faster-than-light travel that aren't impossible?

25:46.100 --> 25:57.200
And where that takes you is this civilization could have zipped out and, to them, only spend a few years in space and come back a few hundred million years later.

25:57.400 --> 25:57.800
Yeah.

25:58.040 --> 25:58.320
Right?

25:58.480 --> 25:58.700
Yeah.

25:58.800 --> 25:59.960
That could be what we're seeing.

26:00.100 --> 26:01.240
It's, is it likely?

26:01.480 --> 26:01.920
No.

26:02.440 --> 26:03.620
But is it impossible?

26:03.800 --> 26:04.560
We can't say.

26:04.820 --> 26:05.020
Yeah.

26:05.020 --> 26:10.020
As she said, we know so little to say that something's impossible is somewhat wrong.

26:10.780 --> 26:13.840
And then, again, when you look at the future, right?

26:13.960 --> 26:16.060
And then you say, well, what about the present?

26:16.840 --> 26:22.300
There's some obvious mundane things like, okay, the Chinese or the Russians have cool stuff we don't understand, which is true.

26:22.660 --> 26:23.100
They do.

26:23.100 --> 26:33.900
But there are other more exotic, really exotic, like, you know, the multi-worlds hypothesis, that there are parallel quantum realms that are splitting off all the time.

26:34.100 --> 26:36.980
And in some of those, could there be some weird things happening?

26:37.340 --> 26:41.720
That one gets a little dicey, I think.

26:41.720 --> 26:54.640
But I think that the more important thing is to break out of the chains of expectation and what we know and just be humble and say there's so much we don't know.

26:55.120 --> 26:59.740
Don't ever rule out something unless you have really hard laboratory proof.

27:00.580 --> 27:01.100
I love that.

27:01.100 --> 27:15.460
And I think if at any point in history you were to see, you know, a repeated anomaly with an abundance of anecdotal evidence, but it didn't comport with the physics of the time, you'd get all these people saying, this can't be true because of physics.

27:15.660 --> 27:17.140
And those people would be wrong.

27:17.140 --> 27:23.180
And the people just saying, we got to follow the evidence and look at the anomaly itself would end up being vindicated.

27:23.480 --> 27:27.800
And there would be some new theory that would come to explain the anomaly.

27:27.800 --> 27:54.540
And per the kind of anthropocentric kind of bias and the extraterrestrial bias, you know, versus time travel, if you were in, you know, kind of North Sentinel Island, which is this remote island that's totally uncontacted, that's, you know, technically part of India, but, you know, has never been contacted outside of a few missionaries where I believe, you know, they've been trying to evangelize Christianity.

27:54.540 --> 27:59.920
You know, these missionaries, you know, I think in certain cases have met tragic ends.

28:00.120 --> 28:03.940
They go and, you know, they get speared or something or, you know, shot with a bow and arrow.

28:04.600 --> 28:15.660
And you always, I wonder, you know, do the North Sentinelese have legends of aliens coming and contacting them when in fact it's just, you know, human beings nearby?

28:15.660 --> 28:18.840
And so that just cuts to this perceptual bias.

28:18.960 --> 28:23.660
And to the time travel thing, Kurt Gerdel had this, you know, model for time travel.

28:23.800 --> 28:33.040
And then Frank Tipler, who is a contemporary of Wheeler and a physicist, shrunk down the Gerdel time travel model.

28:33.280 --> 28:35.780
And it was, he had his thing called the Tipler disc.

28:36.280 --> 28:37.580
And it's a flying saucer.

28:37.760 --> 28:39.580
So I find that fascinating too.

28:39.580 --> 28:52.440
Yeah, yeah, well, I think the main point we want to make is that when we want to study something, the first thing you study is the thing that self is studying it, meaning us.

28:52.980 --> 29:02.340
To look at that instrument and be very clear about its limitations and its strengths so that you are more tempered in the conclusions that you reach.

29:02.340 --> 29:09.640
If you say this instrument isn't seeing something, it could be interpreted as the thing isn't there or the instrument can't see it.

29:10.340 --> 29:13.520
And there's too little of that kind of thinking.

29:14.040 --> 29:15.620
And I'll just give you an example.

29:17.400 --> 29:18.620
Hawking radiation.

29:19.360 --> 29:28.920
Hawking radiation, we believe, is due to particle-antiparticle pairs popping out of the void, whatever that is,

29:28.920 --> 29:34.640
kind of the vacuum-quantum field that's seething with energy.

29:35.000 --> 29:39.160
There is no such thing as nothing, according to modern cosmology.

29:39.900 --> 29:45.760
And these particle-antiparticle pairs normally pop out of the void, whatever that is,

29:46.460 --> 29:51.300
recombined where the matter-antimatter completely annihilate, leaving some residual energy,

29:51.720 --> 29:55.420
which is one of the theories of dark energy that's pushing the universe apart.

29:55.420 --> 30:03.680
And if these particle-antiparticle pairs pop out of nothingness on opposite sides of the event horizon,

30:04.980 --> 30:11.820
some of the energy escapes, which is why there is a glow or hawking radiation around a black hole,

30:12.380 --> 30:15.520
and why they think maybe black holes evaporate over time.

30:15.520 --> 30:21.460
And it also solves some loss-of-information paradoxes around black holes,

30:21.620 --> 30:26.160
where physics says you can't create or destroy information in the physics sense.

30:26.400 --> 30:28.640
And maybe this is how that's conserved.

30:29.060 --> 30:31.280
And through entanglement, there are things that go out.

30:31.340 --> 30:36.500
Well, the point I'm trying to get to is, let's suppose that we live in an n-dimensional universe,

30:36.620 --> 30:38.560
four, that we can see, but there are many more.

30:38.560 --> 30:46.540
So imagine the analogy of a three-dimensional universe interacting with someone who only lives in two dimensions.

30:46.960 --> 30:51.140
So if all we saw was two dimensions, everything would be in a flat plane.

30:51.220 --> 30:52.560
There would be lines, right?

30:52.880 --> 30:59.880
So let's say I'm a three-dimensional person, and I have the surface of the water, which is two dimensions.

31:00.140 --> 31:04.240
And I put my five fingers, well, four fingers and one thumb through it.

31:04.240 --> 31:13.020
The two-dimensional being is going to experience me as five circles, because that's where I intersect its reality.

31:14.240 --> 31:23.460
So when you look at these quantum things popping in and out, that could be something as simple as if we were a plane,

31:23.840 --> 31:28.020
and there was something circling that hit us every now and then.

31:28.080 --> 31:29.680
We would see it pop in and pop out.

31:30.400 --> 31:33.920
But it's only because we don't see the three-dimensional reality.

31:33.920 --> 31:37.620
We only see the two-dimensional reality of something popping in and popping out.

31:37.980 --> 31:45.800
And so that is where if we relax the assumption that there are four dimensions, whatever a dimension is,

31:45.840 --> 31:53.180
and there are more, a lot of things now might make sense, like something moving in impossible ways.

31:53.960 --> 31:56.860
Yes, in three dimensions or four, that could be impossible.

31:57.280 --> 32:00.760
But in five or six or seven, it could be totally possible.

32:00.760 --> 32:06.920
And that's why we really have to open up our minds when we look at UFOs and say,

32:07.040 --> 32:10.260
it makes no sense in our framework.

32:10.480 --> 32:13.080
And that, to me, says our framework is wrong.

32:13.880 --> 32:17.820
We've talked a bit about longevity and life extension on this show.

32:18.360 --> 32:24.040
Extending your telomeres, metabolic optimization, and the through line is always the same.

32:24.040 --> 32:30.040
Most of what determines how long you live comes down to really basic stuff, not these more exotic treatments.

32:30.860 --> 32:38.120
I think about that sometimes when I realize it's 10 p.m. and I haven't eaten all day because I was deep in prep for the next episode,

32:38.400 --> 32:40.680
which is kind of the story of my life since I moved to Austin.

32:40.960 --> 32:46.980
Occasionally, I'll be so deep in work that I'll forget to eat, and then I end up demolishing whatever's closest at midnight.

