Make healthier eating easy with Factor.

33:39.140 --> 33:41.480
Our framework is wrong.

33:41.780 --> 33:43.180
We're seeing something real.

33:44.320 --> 33:49.500
We don't understand it, so we better start questioning our whole understanding of reality.

33:49.500 --> 33:56.340
There's a really cool professor named James Madden who wrote a book called Unidentified Hyperobjects.

33:56.340 --> 34:02.720
And hyperobject is a platonic idea of objects that exist in higher dimensional space like tesseracts.

34:03.300 --> 34:06.700
And you would just see kind of the shadow of these tesseracts.

34:06.700 --> 34:12.140
And if you take this pen and you put it through 2D paper, all you see is a disk.

34:12.340 --> 34:21.700
And so I wonder, you know, in his model, it's like these objects show up in order to almost break your priors specifically.

34:21.700 --> 34:28.920
Like there is this, the wow factor that is on the human side is the intended effect.

34:29.320 --> 34:36.060
And the sort of, there is some sort of like almost intermittent reinforcement or conditioning going on where it's there.

34:36.180 --> 34:41.220
It appears, it, you know, excites you and then you keep going or something.

34:41.220 --> 34:52.020
And it's, it's this sort of synchronistic thing and it's impossible to, you know, kind of separate the observed and the observer, which we, you obviously would do in traditional science.

34:52.720 --> 34:54.180
Well, you know, it's fascinating about that.

34:54.220 --> 34:57.200
And it gets back to something Dr. Gilbert was saying about the motivations.

34:58.200 --> 35:05.560
What is, I, as I told you before the, we started, I was a therapist and as therapists, we try never to tell a patient anything.

35:05.560 --> 35:11.240
We need them to discover it on themselves or they won't quote, get it in their gut.

35:11.540 --> 35:14.540
People only understand that which they themselves discover.

35:14.940 --> 35:16.460
You can't tell people anything.

35:16.580 --> 35:19.520
There's this great book called, if you see the Buddha on the road, kill them.

35:20.040 --> 35:21.280
No one can tell you anything.

35:21.400 --> 35:22.740
You have to discover it for yourself.

35:22.940 --> 35:26.340
So what if extraterrestrials are here to teach us?

35:27.180 --> 35:28.340
This is their mission.

35:29.280 --> 35:33.960
They want to bring intelligent life in the universe up to a kind of a standard level.

35:33.960 --> 35:38.400
So we can join a galactic federation, or maybe they just are altruistic missionaries or something.

35:39.000 --> 35:45.060
And these events are anomalies that they keep introducing to say, hey, pay attention.

35:45.660 --> 35:49.120
There's something over here that tells you you're not looking at things right.

35:49.340 --> 35:59.760
Like maybe there are in dimensions and we're going to keep hitting you with these things until someone says, hmm, maybe this is telling us about our own ignorance on purpose.

35:59.760 --> 36:08.860
So, I mean, I'm not saying that's a case, but that's the kind of thing that we would never normally think about because we wouldn't behave that way.

36:08.860 --> 36:18.280
It's like in Star Trek, the prime directive, you can't kind of openly commune unless, you know, if you're pre-warp drive or you're not up to a certain consciousness level or whatever.

36:18.540 --> 36:20.800
And you might use these tactics.

36:21.120 --> 36:28.100
Maybe it's like cellular automata or something where it's like, you know, this kind of biological network.

36:28.100 --> 36:40.380
And you're hitting a little node with a little wow factor they tell their friends, you know, and then it's sort of you're influencing the teleology of the entire kind of, you know, Petri dish, you know, with these little appearances.

36:41.000 --> 36:41.460
Well, it's funny.

36:41.580 --> 36:44.080
We'll get into this later when we talk about the shadow of time.

36:44.280 --> 36:52.300
But we talk about a hyper-intelligent entity who has learned the hard way to have a very light touch because the universe is very complicated.

36:52.300 --> 36:56.300
And the slightest thing you do here could have a huge effect there.

36:57.100 --> 37:06.000
And so this creature realizes that and kind of works within the system to cause something they want to happen.

37:06.480 --> 37:09.100
And so there is some of that in our book.

37:09.100 --> 37:23.320
But I think that, again, just to kind of summarize the new science of UFOs, what we try to do in there is look into the negative space and to take people at a place they've never been before.

37:23.320 --> 37:40.560
And also to expose people not to the James Bond kind of side of the spy business, but the analytic, academic kind of intellectual side of it, which is, okay, we have spies that collect the information, but then how do we make sense of it?

37:41.160 --> 37:51.860
And when you look at intelligence failures, such as 9-11, Pearl Harbor, and so forth, with one exception, which is we missed the Indian nuclear program, that was a failure of collection.

37:51.860 --> 37:53.080
We just didn't have the data.

37:53.320 --> 37:55.720
But in every other case, we've had the information.

37:56.080 --> 37:58.400
We just didn't know what was staring us in the face.

37:59.500 --> 38:09.620
That's what, I mean, to me, that's why this whole idea of disclosure, I don't know if you saw this, but the White House just registered aliens.gov, which I found to be pretty funny.

38:09.700 --> 38:18.900
I don't know if you guys have a take there, but this whole idea of disclosure is kind of a misnomer to me because I think this space, there's a ton of data.

38:18.900 --> 38:23.760
There's a ton of asymmetric data on the government side, but the sense-making is totally lacking.

38:23.980 --> 38:34.760
And so you have all these file releases going on now with JFK and MLK and Epstein and stuff, but nobody, it's like finding a needle in a haystack and nobody knows how to make sense of what's going on.

38:34.760 --> 38:43.100
And to me, if you can't make sense of those things, which are like conventional, prosaic, political things, good luck with UFOs.

38:43.100 --> 38:45.160
Well, I think AI is going to help that.

38:45.520 --> 38:45.840
True.

38:46.260 --> 38:51.360
I will tell you that the biggest problem in the intelligence world is not collecting.

38:51.760 --> 38:53.620
It's understanding what you've collected.

38:54.220 --> 38:57.240
And, you know, there's so many reasons for that.

38:57.300 --> 38:59.780
There's the volume, velocity, and variety of information.

39:00.020 --> 39:01.920
It goes up exponentially every day.

39:02.740 --> 39:03.200
Right?

39:03.260 --> 39:04.580
There's a lot more information out there.

39:04.700 --> 39:04.880
Yeah.

39:04.880 --> 39:10.320
And then, yeah, so the real frontier in intelligence is to understand.

39:10.320 --> 39:15.260
Yeah, except the problem with AI is that AI is trained by humans.

39:15.540 --> 39:27.980
So if any AI is trained by humans to detect one or two things, it's not going to see the thing called X that will appear out of nowhere.

39:28.260 --> 39:28.700
That's right.

39:28.820 --> 39:30.620
So it will miss it also.

39:30.860 --> 39:31.280
That's right.

39:31.280 --> 39:31.720
Yes.

39:32.120 --> 39:40.020
Yeah, if that low sample size, an AI classifier is going to mistake something, then at high sample size, it's still going to mistake it.

39:40.180 --> 39:48.860
And you need some sort of human supervised learning component in the loop to actually have good signal on the anomalies that are correct.

39:48.940 --> 39:51.360
And then you train up the model or something.

39:51.680 --> 39:52.240
Yeah, yeah.

39:52.580 --> 39:58.000
But a good intelligence analyst will be humble and look outside the lampposts.

39:58.000 --> 39:59.940
In other words, be aware of their own biases.

39:59.940 --> 40:04.220
There's this great book called The Psychology of Intelligence Analysis by Richard Hoyers.

40:04.800 --> 40:07.420
All analysts are taught to read it.

40:07.480 --> 40:08.280
It's part of our training.

40:08.920 --> 40:10.480
And it's to look at our own instrument.

40:10.600 --> 40:15.140
And he talks about all the different biases, confirmation bias, you know, and so forth.

40:15.140 --> 40:26.320
And it's true that AI is just, you know, it's like a Ferrari that'll go now a million miles an hour instead of 200 miles an hour.

40:26.400 --> 40:27.380
But it's still a Ferrari.

40:27.800 --> 40:28.100
Right.

40:28.220 --> 40:31.420
You know, it's not going to go into the air or go below the water.

40:31.420 --> 40:34.420
And there are things like you mentioned time.

40:34.800 --> 40:47.640
Time to me is so interesting because it's like the, you know, there's a David Foster Wallace speech and it's like these goldfish talking to each other and they're trying to conceptualize water.

40:47.780 --> 40:49.800
But water is the medium in which they swim.

40:49.860 --> 40:51.620
And that feels like time in many ways.

40:51.620 --> 40:54.240
It's the most used noun in the English language.

40:54.760 --> 40:58.620
And yet it's always defined with respect to something else.

40:58.940 --> 41:06.100
So macroscopically, the movement of bodies and then microscopically, you know, oscillations on an electromagnetic wave.

41:06.520 --> 41:15.880
And you get into things like, you know, Einstein, you know, Einstein's equations or even Maxwell's equations, I believe, work the same way forwards as they do backwards.

41:15.880 --> 41:25.520
And, you know, you have time treated as a formal axiom or as a classical axiom, rather, in Schrodinger's equation.

41:26.100 --> 41:33.060
And so it's, but, but, but, but, but there's all sorts of possible time weirdness and certain quantum interpretations, obviously, of temporal non-locality.

41:33.300 --> 41:38.380
And so it is, that seems like a very interesting foray into studying the UFO stuff.

41:38.380 --> 41:56.400
Yeah, I mean, there is, for example, one minority theory that the Big Bang spawned a matter universe, which went one direction in time, and a simultaneous equal one, an anti-matter universe, going in the other direction in time.

41:56.740 --> 41:58.100
Is this the Sakharov?

41:58.280 --> 41:59.580
I don't know who is that.

41:59.680 --> 42:01.240
I just remember reading that.

42:01.240 --> 42:11.380
And there are other theories, we live inside this huge, supermassive black hole, and there's some weird paradoxes, like the more massive the black hole, the less likely tidal forces will stretch you apart.

42:12.340 --> 42:14.940
The math is very complicated, but that's true.

42:15.060 --> 42:20.700
So it could be that what we call the universe is just what we see inside this big black hole, and how would we know?

42:21.080 --> 42:21.480
Right?

42:21.560 --> 42:26.480
I mean, I think that at the end of the day, if we ever know the truth, which I don't think we will.

42:26.920 --> 42:27.460
You don't?

42:27.620 --> 42:29.740
Well, no, this is a conversation I had with Marvin Minsky.

42:30.000 --> 42:30.300
Okay.

42:30.300 --> 42:33.460
And I said, Marvin, are we as humans...

42:33.460 --> 42:38.100
For the audience, by the way, Marvin Minsky is kind of the godfather of modern artificial intelligence.

42:38.160 --> 42:38.560
Right, MIT.

42:38.780 --> 42:39.120
MIT.

42:39.420 --> 42:52.080
And I knew him quite well, and I love kind of BSing with him, and kind of like you did in the dorm, you know, with your refreshment, like, oh, man, this thing's all connected, everything.

42:52.420 --> 42:59.820
Well, I said, Marvin, are humans either collectively or individually capable of understanding nature in its entirety?

42:59.820 --> 43:01.200
And he goes, of course not.

43:01.980 --> 43:02.980
I'll give you an example.

43:03.080 --> 43:07.360
My cat over there is the smartest cat I know or have even ever heard of.

43:07.440 --> 43:08.560
It is a genius cat.

43:08.720 --> 43:10.020
I'll never teach it French.

43:11.480 --> 43:11.880
Right.

43:11.880 --> 43:20.320
And it turns out that was wrong, too, because we now know that some cats can understand about 400 words of a language.

43:20.320 --> 43:30.000
But the point is that it's hubris to think that at whatever level of intelligence we've achieved is enough to understand nature.

43:30.180 --> 43:30.420
Yeah.

43:30.720 --> 43:31.280
Right?

43:31.480 --> 43:31.720
Yeah.

43:31.720 --> 43:40.300
Well, it's like, you know, whales and dolphins and elephants and parrots are, like, way smarter than we ever thought they were.

43:40.520 --> 43:40.960
Crows.

43:41.160 --> 43:41.440
Mm-hmm.

43:42.140 --> 43:46.420
You know, a crow will remember your face for two decades and come after you if you pissed it off.

43:46.520 --> 43:47.120
It's wild.

43:47.180 --> 43:47.320
Right?

43:47.360 --> 43:49.940
I mean, animals are way smarter than we think they are.

43:50.320 --> 43:54.660
But do we really think we can explain partial differential equations to a parrot?

43:54.860 --> 43:55.100
Maybe.

43:55.240 --> 43:55.680
Maybe not.

43:55.780 --> 43:56.480
Probably not.

43:56.640 --> 43:56.900
Right.

43:56.900 --> 44:03.960
And so it stands to reason that there's way more to be known than our brains could ever comprehend.

44:04.460 --> 44:08.760
And to me, that's the exciting thing about UAPs and UFOs.

44:08.940 --> 44:13.320
It's nature's way of reminding us how little we know.

44:13.920 --> 44:18.480
And Isaac Asimov said, science doesn't proceed with eureka.

44:18.600 --> 44:20.500
Like, oh, you get this great insight.

44:20.820 --> 44:23.280
It proceeds with, that's funny.

44:23.280 --> 44:30.680
You know, because that's funny means, hmm, that makes no sense compared to what I think I know.

44:30.860 --> 44:35.860
And whenever you see something that doesn't fit what you know, a real scientist should get excited.

44:36.600 --> 44:37.280
Not skeptical.

44:38.320 --> 44:38.620
Yeah.

44:38.840 --> 44:43.260
But as Max Planck said, science precedes one funeral at a time.

44:43.400 --> 44:43.960
Right.

44:44.120 --> 44:44.640
Right.

44:45.340 --> 44:45.600
Yeah.

44:45.600 --> 44:54.300
Well, accepting that caveat around kind of having epistemic humility, you guys have done this amazing survey level overview.

44:54.520 --> 45:00.480
Do you guys have kind of a base case for what's going on, even if it's a soup of things?

45:01.340 --> 45:02.900
Well, yes and no.

45:03.240 --> 45:11.420
Yes, in that we believe when you look at all the many thousands of reports, and we've looked at all, and some I have guilty knowledge of from when I was inside the government.

45:11.420 --> 45:25.200
There is a tiny, tiny, tiny fraction, maybe a few dozen out of all the many tens or hundreds of thousands, where I feel confident saying there's something real there.

45:26.240 --> 45:31.740
It's not an artifact of who observed it, of the instrument, of some mistake.

45:31.820 --> 45:32.420
It's real.

45:32.620 --> 45:34.920
And it's something we do not understand.

45:34.920 --> 45:35.920
Mm-hmm.

45:35.920 --> 45:36.120
Right.

45:36.460 --> 45:41.420
And so that, to me, is why we are so passionate about this.

45:41.520 --> 45:44.000
Because as scientists, that excites us.

45:44.140 --> 45:44.620
Mm-hmm.

45:44.620 --> 45:46.600
We are not threatened by it.

45:46.660 --> 45:48.040
We are not repelled by it.

45:48.100 --> 45:49.300
We are drawn to it.

45:49.440 --> 45:49.820
Mm-hmm.

45:49.820 --> 45:54.740
And so I guess I shouldn't say this, but you can comment for yourself.

45:54.740 --> 45:58.380
But I'm kind of on a mission to get serious scientists to take a look at this.

45:58.460 --> 45:58.720
Mm-hmm.

45:58.720 --> 46:06.760
Because right now, it's very hard, because there's the giggle factor, there's the, oh, UFO, alien, little green man.

46:06.760 --> 46:17.680
And so really, the world's best scientists, with a few exceptions, like Levy and Harvard and places like that, they're staying away from it because it's a career killer.

46:18.140 --> 46:19.500
That's what it seems like.

46:19.780 --> 46:27.140
And then simultaneously, you have, you know, you obviously were as high up as it gets in the U.S. government when it came to science.

46:27.240 --> 46:28.760
You were kind of the CTO of the country.

46:29.120 --> 46:45.620
And then you have this movie, I don't know if you've seen this, The Age of Disclosure, where you have guys like Jim Semivan, you know, high up at the CIA, or Chris Mellon, who is Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Intelligence, you know, also cleared to a lot of stuff.

46:45.620 --> 46:50.000
And they're saying we have a program that's like reverse engineering this stuff.

46:50.340 --> 46:51.940
What do you guys think there?

46:52.020 --> 46:53.440
Do you think that's legit?

46:53.660 --> 46:56.160
Well, I got to be careful what I say here.

46:57.200 --> 46:59.980
I was, I had access to a whole lot of stuff.

47:00.220 --> 47:00.340
Yeah.

47:00.440 --> 47:01.160
I never saw that.

47:01.400 --> 47:01.700
Okay.

47:01.840 --> 47:03.140
I never saw anything like that.

47:03.260 --> 47:06.800
I, we have this thing, we say, yo, explain yo.

47:07.640 --> 47:10.200
It's maybe yes, maybe no, yo.

47:10.900 --> 47:14.800
Yeah, when presented, we call it the power of yo.

47:15.040 --> 47:15.360
Okay.

47:15.360 --> 47:19.400
When presented with something, don't say yes, don't say no, say yo.

47:19.640 --> 47:19.940
Okay.

47:20.140 --> 47:21.420
Maybe yes, maybe no.

47:21.720 --> 47:22.920
Keep an open mind.

47:23.040 --> 47:23.540
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

47:23.580 --> 47:25.700
And so, I don't have any illusions.

47:25.920 --> 47:29.080
It's just because I should have known everything that I did.

47:29.280 --> 47:32.180
I know for a fact that people hide things.

47:32.320 --> 47:32.600
Right.

47:32.700 --> 47:36.340
You know, and so, the fact that I didn't know it doesn't mean it wasn't there.

47:36.640 --> 47:36.840
Yeah.

47:36.980 --> 47:38.520
You see, this is a fascinating thing.

47:39.120 --> 47:42.880
Your average layperson, when they look at the government saying, we're not going to release

47:42.880 --> 47:46.680
this UFO thing, thinks, ah, because they don't want us to know about aliens, but they don't

47:46.680 --> 47:47.720
think about other motivations.

47:48.120 --> 47:48.940
I'll give you one.

47:49.720 --> 47:55.340
Let's say we have sensors of a certain kind that are way better than we want anyone to

47:55.340 --> 47:56.020
know they are.

47:56.020 --> 47:56.300
Right.

47:57.500 --> 48:01.320
Because we don't want the adversary to know, oh, we can see X, Y, or Z.

48:01.860 --> 48:03.640
That's called sources and methods.

48:04.080 --> 48:07.480
And in the intelligence world, that's what we protect more than anything.

48:07.880 --> 48:11.100
We can't let the adversary know what we know we can know.

48:11.620 --> 48:16.180
And so, I have no doubt that some of the reluctance to release some of the stuff, it

48:16.180 --> 48:19.980
was captured by a collection system that we don't want people to know we have.

48:21.180 --> 48:21.860
Yeah, that makes sense.

48:21.860 --> 48:25.760
They can see farther, longer, and the wavelengths that they didn't know that we could, and so

48:25.760 --> 48:25.980
forth.

48:26.200 --> 48:31.020
And I think some of the data captures have been through those kind of systems.

48:32.100 --> 48:36.740
And that just to reveal that can reveal the capability that we have.

48:37.220 --> 48:40.500
And so, I feel quite certain that there's some of that going on.

48:41.100 --> 48:42.880
Yeah, no, I mean, that makes total sense.

48:43.160 --> 48:47.760
You mentioned also Navy patents around laser polygraphy.

48:47.760 --> 48:48.260
Oh, yes.

48:48.520 --> 48:55.220
Yeah, well, this is interesting, because in looking at the possibilities, I just start

48:55.220 --> 48:56.680
from first principles of physics.

48:56.880 --> 49:02.340
If something is moving really, really fast with a super acceleration, the most fundamental

49:02.340 --> 49:04.800
equation in physics is F equals MA.

49:05.100 --> 49:08.180
Force equals mass time is acceleration, right?

49:08.180 --> 49:14.020
And so, if you look at an extraordinary acceleration, there are two ways to look at it.

49:14.220 --> 49:19.860
There's an unbelievable force, or there's very low mass, or both.

49:20.540 --> 49:22.000
And you say, well, what could do that?

49:22.300 --> 49:26.300
Well, when I was at Disney, we were developing electronic fireworks.

49:26.300 --> 49:35.520
And the way we did it is we had a Q-switch neodymium YAG laser that we focused to a spot in the atmosphere.

49:35.860 --> 49:42.380
And we put so much energy there that we ionized the air and created ball lightning, okay?

49:42.480 --> 49:49.480
And then we moved it around with mirrors and lenses so that we created voxels in open space.

49:49.740 --> 49:53.960
And we could move those around like fireworks or like anything else, okay?

49:53.960 --> 50:00.580
Those little plasmas reflect RF energy and give off tremendous heat and obviously a visual

50:00.580 --> 50:01.040
signature.

50:01.940 --> 50:06.520
So, I thought, well, that has essentially zero mass.

50:06.820 --> 50:12.520
If I were going to fake it on purpose, and that is, by the way, one of the things we look

50:12.520 --> 50:17.180
at in the book, if someone was consciously going about faking something to make you think

50:17.180 --> 50:21.340
there was a UFO, for whatever reason, like the Russians do this all the time.

50:21.420 --> 50:22.460
They call it Moskerovka.

50:22.460 --> 50:27.160
They make us think they can do things that we never thought they could do to deter us.

50:28.100 --> 50:28.420
Right?

50:28.820 --> 50:33.400
And so, I asked, this is what I used to do at Disney, fake things.

50:33.600 --> 50:37.880
And I talked to this guy, Cliff Wong, who was the world's expert on drones.

50:37.940 --> 50:40.360
And I said, if you wanted to fake X, Y, or Z, how would you do it?

50:41.040 --> 50:42.280
And so, he told me.

50:42.760 --> 50:48.020
He said, well, what I do is I would have a big, a huge balloon here that was towed by a

50:48.020 --> 50:51.820
little teeny drone, and you'd think it was this big orb when, in fact, it wasn't.

50:52.240 --> 50:52.280
Right?

50:52.400 --> 50:53.780
So, we get into all the ways of fake.

50:53.860 --> 51:02.360
But getting back to the plasma, I said, these glowing orbs could be free space plasmids that

51:02.360 --> 51:03.520
are being directed by a laser.

51:03.760 --> 51:04.020
Right.

51:04.180 --> 51:08.080
Well, it turned out there's a Navy patent to do exactly that, to draw things in the shape

51:08.080 --> 51:10.040
of an airplane, to fool missiles.

51:10.440 --> 51:15.020
And it would be, it would look like it's accelerating at, you know, crazy G's.

51:15.260 --> 51:15.420
Yeah.

51:15.500 --> 51:19.680
And it would do everything that these orbs are doing.

51:20.000 --> 51:23.580
Seems like it's breaking conservation momentum, but it's just massless.

51:23.580 --> 51:24.480
It has zero mass.

51:24.580 --> 51:24.760
Right.

51:24.760 --> 51:28.920
If something is moving in a way that no mass could, maybe it doesn't have any mass.

51:28.920 --> 51:29.780
Maybe it doesn't have mass.

51:29.880 --> 51:31.460
Maybe that's the way to look at it.

51:31.600 --> 51:31.740
Yeah.

51:31.740 --> 51:36.480
Well, if you were to look at, let's say, the Nimitz 2004 case, which I know you guys are

51:36.480 --> 51:37.380
pretty familiar with.

51:37.380 --> 51:39.700
And the Roosevelt and the Omaha and yeah, yeah.

51:39.700 --> 51:40.020
Exactly.

51:40.580 --> 51:40.760
Yeah.

51:40.820 --> 51:41.460
In 2015.

51:41.760 --> 51:47.080
So in 2004, you have, you know, Nimitz off the coast of San Diego, you have solar carrier

51:47.080 --> 51:53.340
strike group, you have radar, you have, you know, eyewitness observation, and then you

51:53.340 --> 51:56.660
have thermal imaging that's been released, this forward-looking infrared.

51:57.060 --> 51:58.280
And CCTV also.

51:58.520 --> 51:59.060
And CCTV.

51:59.060 --> 52:05.840
And so would this sort of plasma ball configuration be able to account for all of that?

52:06.100 --> 52:06.460
Yes.

52:06.460 --> 52:13.700
Yes, it would from a kinematic point of view, but the visuals don't line up.

52:14.040 --> 52:15.020
Those are tic-tacs.

52:16.020 --> 52:22.220
And the plasmas actually can look like a tic-tac because they're not actual balls normally the

52:22.220 --> 52:27.200
way you do them unless you really are good with adaptive optics.

52:27.200 --> 52:32.040
But generally what happens with these plasmas, it's a laser beam coming to a focus.

52:32.380 --> 52:32.460
Yeah.

52:32.560 --> 52:38.700
And what happens is instead of just a ball, you tend to get the actual caustic of the

52:38.700 --> 52:40.040
energy coming in like this.

52:40.100 --> 52:42.860
So you'll see kind of a rope of energy like this.

52:43.140 --> 52:44.860
And that could look like a tic-tac.

52:44.860 --> 52:51.220
And then when you take into account atmospheric scattering and stuff, I would say possibly.

52:51.600 --> 52:55.340
It wouldn't be my first hypothesis because they define it.

52:55.420 --> 52:58.320
It looks like it's made of white plastic or something.

52:59.920 --> 53:03.100
Under normal conditions, these plasmas wouldn't look that way.

53:03.100 --> 53:03.540
Okay.

53:03.820 --> 53:05.820
But they also are louder than hell.

53:05.900 --> 53:09.940
In fact, when Mike Leisner, the CEO of Disney, I first showed him these things.

53:11.440 --> 53:13.660
He said, oh, we're not going to do this.

53:14.320 --> 53:16.280
It's really impressive, but we're not doing this.

53:16.340 --> 53:16.900
And I said, why?

53:16.980 --> 53:21.160
He said, Eric, there's something profoundly disturbing about the air over your head catching

53:21.160 --> 53:21.560
fire.

53:21.800 --> 53:26.480
And yeah, we like to stimulate our guests, but we don't want them running screaming out

53:26.480 --> 53:26.820
of the building.

53:27.420 --> 53:28.700
And it's really loud.

53:28.820 --> 53:29.380
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

53:29.380 --> 53:32.200
It's really loud because it creates sonic booms.

53:32.200 --> 53:38.020
You know, and so, you know, it's part of it.

53:38.220 --> 53:40.480
But what I do, what we do in the book is just-

53:40.480 --> 53:44.120
But that sounds like a pretty good capability for like a PSYOP or something.

53:44.300 --> 53:44.700
Well, it is, yeah.

53:44.700 --> 53:49.900
If you want to do something on foreign land, you know, ace in the old tech or whatever,

53:50.120 --> 53:55.500
you, you know, fire in the sky and, you know, some plasma projection balls everywhere and

53:55.500 --> 53:56.520
things like that.

53:56.540 --> 53:57.240
Well, that's right.

53:57.300 --> 54:00.020
I mean, let's get back to the faking theory.

54:00.020 --> 54:05.020
If someone isn't doing it and you're noticing it, they're doing it on purpose to mess with

54:05.020 --> 54:05.460
your head.

54:06.040 --> 54:09.520
And the Russians in particular really do a lot of this.

54:09.840 --> 54:10.000
Do they?

54:10.120 --> 54:16.180
And because Patton said it, weapons change, but man who uses them changes not at all.

54:16.340 --> 54:18.460
To defeat an enemy, you don't defeat their weapons.

54:18.580 --> 54:21.400
You defend, you defeat their brain and their heart.

54:21.920 --> 54:24.200
You erode their will to fight.

54:24.800 --> 54:25.900
The Russians know this.

54:25.900 --> 54:27.400
They don't have the resources we do.

54:27.900 --> 54:32.820
So one of the things they do is make us think they can do things that make us think twice

54:32.820 --> 54:33.760
about messing with them.

54:34.540 --> 54:37.220
And so it is in, I'm not saying they're doing this.

54:37.260 --> 54:42.360
I'm saying it would be consistent with their modus operandi to be messing with our heads.

54:42.620 --> 54:46.320
And by the way, when it comes to directed energy, there's no one better in the world than

54:46.320 --> 54:46.800
the Russians.

54:46.800 --> 54:53.620
You know, Bozov and the laser, you could say they invented it, you know, and they are really

54:53.620 --> 54:54.680
good at directed energy.

54:54.840 --> 54:57.440
I mean, that's what Havana syndrome is all about, directed energy.

54:57.620 --> 55:05.160
So I think it's entirely possible that some of these phenomena are a foreign actor deliberately

55:05.160 --> 55:06.120
messing with our head.

55:06.120 --> 55:06.600
Interesting.

55:07.140 --> 55:14.960
Yeah, there's, I think it's 1976 SALT talks, and it's Kissinger is talking to Dobrynin,

55:15.220 --> 55:17.800
who's the, you know, foreign minister from the Soviets.

55:18.280 --> 55:22.320
And he's saying, stop beaming our embassy with microwaves.

55:22.480 --> 55:26.040
You've been, you know, blasting it for, you know, 12 hours straight.

55:26.220 --> 55:31.980
And Walter Stossel, who's the American ambassador, was, you know, not only hurt by this, he ends

55:31.980 --> 55:34.520
up dying of kind of a rare form of blood cancer.

55:34.520 --> 55:38.820
And so if that's going on in the seventies, and then it feels like we've had all this,

55:38.940 --> 55:45.260
like, honestly gaslighting on the part of, you know, CIA, a lot of people, a lot of diplomats

55:45.260 --> 55:49.320
who are stationed abroad, who are experiencing these things that, you know, they're consistently

55:49.320 --> 55:51.900
called psychosomatic or crazy or whatever.

55:51.900 --> 55:57.320
And then you have this Der Spiegel 60 Minutes, you know, report saying, no, this is all real.

55:57.320 --> 55:59.340
And the Soviets have been doing it for decades.

55:59.980 --> 56:02.220
Well, you really, we're deep into that.

56:02.220 --> 56:06.400
And I mean, I've been, I can't say exactly, but I'm very much part of that investigation.

56:06.400 --> 56:07.840
And so is Dr. Gilbert.

56:08.000 --> 56:11.160
Yeah, we've been interviewing victims of Havana syndrome.

56:11.560 --> 56:11.720
Yeah.

56:11.840 --> 56:19.940
And it's spectacular because nobody understands that there are a series of symptoms that are

56:19.940 --> 56:23.620
all linked together that people don't understand that are just unique.

56:23.620 --> 56:30.180
But there are a lot of people, there are like over 1,000 U.S. officials, you know, from State

56:30.180 --> 56:36.320
Department and other American personnel, there are family members, there are children also

56:36.320 --> 56:45.140
that have reported, it's called anomalous health incidents now, A-H-I, which is Havana syndrome,

56:45.720 --> 56:46.040
you know.

56:46.040 --> 56:52.240
And people are usually in their 20s, 30s, 40s, they're in great physical shape.

56:53.460 --> 57:01.020
And, but the, the, the, the symptoms started when they were stationed in Cuba or Russia or

57:01.020 --> 57:03.860
China, Austria, Germany, Switzerland.

57:04.100 --> 57:08.580
And there are a lot of them in the United States and near the White House also.

57:08.580 --> 57:16.000
And, and people are staying at hotels, apartment offices, or sometimes in their, in their cars.

57:16.660 --> 57:21.960
But, but there are puzzling combinations of symptoms that we've, we've never seen before.

57:22.180 --> 57:31.640
So a few people described like dizziness, combination of dizziness, headache, hearing loud, high frequency,

57:32.220 --> 57:37.700
very directional sounds that seem to come from a specific location.

57:37.700 --> 57:45.300
And both sounds and symptoms disappear when victims leave the room and they reappear when

57:45.300 --> 57:47.560
victims reenter the room, you know.

57:47.700 --> 57:55.480
And some Havana syndrome victims describe disabling cognitive problems like memory problems and

57:55.480 --> 58:03.900
slow processing speed, balance problem, hearing loss, ear pain, tinnitus, insomnia, irritability,

58:03.900 --> 58:05.200
and sometimes depression.

58:05.900 --> 58:11.500
And, and, and the physicians could not understand what was going on.

58:11.500 --> 58:18.760
So we did a lot of studies and we find ENT specialists found that the, that's the otolith inside the

58:18.760 --> 58:23.500
inner ear that get affected consistently in most of those cases.

58:23.500 --> 58:33.200
And now, the otolith, the little, little, little, uh, teeny, uh, uh, bony, bony structures inside the

58:33.200 --> 58:38.480
inner ear that are responsible for balance and those get disrupted.

58:38.480 --> 58:43.140
Uh, and it's very difficult to find, to find what it is.

58:43.220 --> 58:47.200
I mean, people do, they do MRIs and they, they can't find anything.

58:47.200 --> 58:51.940
It's, it's only when you study the otolith of the ears, of the inner ear.

58:51.940 --> 58:57.040
Well, that's the one, uh, cluster of symptoms that seems to be in common with many of them.

58:57.200 --> 59:04.300
And, uh, I'll just say, again, I have to be careful picking my words, but I think there

59:04.300 --> 59:10.260
was not unanimity within the community, the intelligence community on what was going on.

59:10.600 --> 59:15.640
You had one side saying it's real and we know what it is with very high likelihood.

59:15.640 --> 59:16.460
And here it is.

59:17.160 --> 59:21.040
And then you had the other, which was the official version is there's no, they're, they're nothing

59:21.040 --> 59:21.880
to see here folks.

59:22.780 --> 59:28.900
And those of us who are tightly connected on the one side who heard that were shocked,

59:29.260 --> 59:31.160
mortified, angry.

59:31.720 --> 59:32.420
But you saw Dr.

59:32.480 --> 59:39.200
Relman, for example, the Stanford MD, um, uh, I think he said it best.

59:39.320 --> 59:39.460
Yeah.

59:39.640 --> 59:45.460
And, uh, in an essay I just published, I really talk about, again, the psychology of how that

59:45.460 --> 59:45.960
could happen.

59:45.960 --> 59:52.040
And I believe that the people in the intelligence community at state department and CIA who say

59:52.040 --> 59:55.460
there's nothing there, there, I don't think they know it and they're covering it up.

59:56.660 --> 01:00:02.160
I think they don't believe it because I have seen that over and over and over again.

01:00:02.220 --> 01:00:06.960
And at the end of the essay, I quote Upton Sinclair, who said, you can't explain something

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:10.160
to a man whose salary depends on not understanding it.

01:00:10.160 --> 01:00:10.340
Hmm.

01:00:10.880 --> 01:00:11.320
Right.

01:00:11.480 --> 01:00:11.580
Yeah.

01:00:11.580 --> 01:00:15.580
And again, it gets back to the common theme you've heard us talk about, which is whenever

01:00:15.580 --> 01:00:19.520
you have an instrument reporting something, ask about the instrument itself.

01:00:19.740 --> 01:00:20.000
Yeah.

01:00:20.340 --> 01:00:20.520
Right.

01:00:20.620 --> 01:00:24.420
So the people who aren't believing it can't believe it.

01:00:24.580 --> 01:00:24.780
Yeah.

01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:28.040
Because if they believed it, their whole ego structure would fall apart.

01:00:28.160 --> 01:00:28.480
Right.

01:00:28.660 --> 01:00:28.840
Right.

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:30.420
So they have to believe it.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:30.740
Yeah.

01:00:30.840 --> 01:00:33.540
And so I think they truly think there's nothing there.

01:00:34.240 --> 01:00:36.000
Speaking of which, yeah, go for it.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:40.660
And they don't believe that something can happen that they don't understand.

01:00:40.800 --> 01:00:42.720
They think they have to understand everything.

01:00:43.080 --> 01:00:45.120
And if they don't understand it, it doesn't exist.

01:00:45.120 --> 01:00:47.680
But it sure does exist.

01:00:48.020 --> 01:00:51.740
I mean, we have interviewed a number of victims and this is not fake.

01:00:51.820 --> 01:00:53.560
This really, really exists.

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:56.860
And it's devastating for the people.

01:00:57.500 --> 01:00:58.500
One of them used to work for me.

01:00:58.580 --> 01:00:59.720
I know him extremely well.

01:00:59.820 --> 01:01:00.220
Jesus.

01:01:00.620 --> 01:01:03.240
And we had a long conversation with him recently.

01:01:03.240 --> 01:01:08.780
I can't mention his name or where he worked, but what bothers us the most about it is the

01:01:08.780 --> 01:01:10.320
victimizations of the victims.

01:01:10.780 --> 01:01:15.320
Imagine serving your country, being wounded in service of your country, and your country

01:01:15.320 --> 01:01:18.240
says, no, you didn't have that happen, and you're crazy.

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:19.600
It's scary.

01:01:20.240 --> 01:01:20.780
It's awful.

01:01:20.980 --> 01:01:24.160
I mean, to me, actually, and a lot of them will tell you that's the worst part.

