And they were worried.

01:15:44.700 --> 01:15:48.980
So if it's the same thing, and it's something coming from outside Earth that we don't

01:15:48.980 --> 01:15:55.920
understand, if officials acknowledge that this is what is happening, it's going to scare

01:15:55.920 --> 01:15:57.900
the bejesus out of everybody, right?

01:15:58.340 --> 01:15:59.000
Or excite them.

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:05.900
And they don't want to do that, because first, again, they don't understand it, so it doesn't

01:16:05.900 --> 01:16:10.520
exist, because otherwise it will make them look incompetent.

01:16:10.900 --> 01:16:13.320
And it's been going on for several years also.

01:16:13.460 --> 01:16:18.780
So how come they've let this happen for several years without doing anything?

01:16:18.940 --> 01:16:21.660
And the only way is to say it doesn't exist.

01:16:21.660 --> 01:16:27.220
It's not good at the right, not the right orientation towards this whole subject.

01:16:27.340 --> 01:16:32.540
And another thing sort of like that, and I actually think it's more acknowledged probably

01:16:32.540 --> 01:16:35.140
by CIA than it is by the civilian world.

01:16:35.140 --> 01:16:38.000
But there was a psychic spy program.

01:16:38.440 --> 01:16:39.000
This is-

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:39.460
MKUltra.

01:16:39.460 --> 01:16:41.680
Well, there's MKUltra, but there's also Stargate.

01:16:41.820 --> 01:16:42.520
Do you know about this?

01:16:42.800 --> 01:16:43.160
Yeah, yeah.

01:16:43.300 --> 01:16:50.360
And so there's, to me, a bunch of evidence from CIA circles that there is some sort of

01:16:50.360 --> 01:16:55.060
mind-matter connection, or there's, maybe we're talking about kind of transmission theory of

01:16:55.060 --> 01:17:01.680
consciousness, something else going on as far as our epistemological circuitry than anybody

01:17:01.680 --> 01:17:03.220
in academia would ever admit.

01:17:03.220 --> 01:17:09.260
But, and something that I feel very passionate about is, like, science should not be locked

01:17:09.260 --> 01:17:14.840
up in any of these agencies, to the extent that there's some trade secret that confers

01:17:14.840 --> 01:17:16.520
a tactical warfare advantage, fine.

01:17:16.740 --> 01:17:23.180
But the idea that, like, something that fundamental is just, you know, kind of stuck in these agencies,

01:17:23.360 --> 01:17:28.020
and I mean, this is all, by the way, this is FOIA in 2017, these programs are public now.

01:17:28.480 --> 01:17:30.120
But that's pretty wild, right?

01:17:30.120 --> 01:17:33.440
Like, no one in academia would, they'd all laugh at this.

01:17:33.720 --> 01:17:35.960
If we're, you know, they'd laugh at the conversation we're having right now.

01:17:36.480 --> 01:17:41.580
But then the people in aerospace and in these agencies that, like, need every advantage they

01:17:41.580 --> 01:17:45.140
get with intelligence modalities, use it.

01:17:46.400 --> 01:17:47.940
Well, I don't know.

01:17:48.020 --> 01:17:49.120
I wouldn't go that far.

01:17:49.980 --> 01:17:55.540
I will tell you this, the Russians take this stuff way more seriously than we do, to the

01:17:55.540 --> 01:18:00.160
extent that in chess matches, they would have summoning, like, beaming negative mental energy

01:18:00.160 --> 01:18:02.560
at an opponent of a Russian, you know.

01:18:02.840 --> 01:18:07.320
And the Russians are much more open to things that we aren't.

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:09.800
And things that...

01:18:09.800 --> 01:18:10.400
Both good and bad.

01:18:10.520 --> 01:18:13.700
And things that don't cost anything, because they don't have very much...

01:18:13.700 --> 01:18:14.040
That's right.

01:18:14.040 --> 01:18:14.540
The resources.

01:18:15.080 --> 01:18:16.040
No, that's true.

01:18:16.040 --> 01:18:22.180
And I think that some of the biggest discoveries in this area probably will be the Russians,

01:18:22.300 --> 01:18:24.500
because they have much more open minds than we do.

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:28.940
I think they tend to be more spiritual and mystical, maybe, than we do because of their

01:18:28.940 --> 01:18:29.360
history.

01:18:30.120 --> 01:18:37.080
But, you know, let's talk about this remote consciousness thing.

01:18:37.240 --> 01:18:41.220
And these phenomena where a psychic can tell you there's a body buried under a bridge, and

01:18:41.220 --> 01:18:42.820
they go there and, yeah, the body's there.

01:18:42.820 --> 01:18:49.900
One explanation is ESP or clairvoyance or non-local consciousness, and that's possible.

01:18:50.020 --> 01:18:52.320
But then let's look at the other possibilities.

01:18:52.980 --> 01:18:55.700
We know there are some humans that are savants.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:19:02.820
You know, someone who you could say, what day of the week is, you know, 50-55...

01:19:03.620 --> 01:19:04.060
Rain man.

01:19:04.120 --> 01:19:04.880
October, yeah.

01:19:04.960 --> 01:19:05.160
Yeah.

01:19:05.340 --> 01:19:10.820
And so there are some people with unbelievable, weird genius capabilities.

01:19:11.820 --> 01:19:12.140
Yes.

01:19:12.140 --> 01:19:16.980
You know, who's to say that someone couldn't have absorbed all the news and everything

01:19:16.980 --> 01:19:21.100
about the human condition and reached the conclusion that a serial killer of a certain

01:19:21.100 --> 01:19:24.940
kind is going to put a body in a certain place in a certain date, right?

01:19:25.140 --> 01:19:26.920
That this is not ESP.

01:19:27.240 --> 01:19:33.360
It's just elevating an analytic skills to a genius level, right?

01:19:33.360 --> 01:19:40.900
And so, to me, something like that is more likely explanation than something that's totally

01:19:40.900 --> 01:19:42.340
outside any range.

01:19:42.520 --> 01:19:43.740
I would disagree with you.

01:19:43.820 --> 01:19:46.200
Well, but I always look at...

01:19:46.200 --> 01:19:50.460
You have to respect what we don't know, and I'm not going to say impossible.

01:19:50.740 --> 01:19:51.120
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:19:51.120 --> 01:19:52.140
I would go that far.

01:19:52.140 --> 01:19:58.400
But at the same time, I am a scientist, and I look at, evaluate possibilities based on

01:19:58.400 --> 01:20:04.060
the best tools we have available to come up with, is there an explanation within the

01:20:04.060 --> 01:20:04.980
science we do know?

01:20:04.980 --> 01:20:06.380
And I would start there.

01:20:06.920 --> 01:20:12.620
And then to posit a science we don't know is such an unknown realm, it's almost not worth

01:20:12.620 --> 01:20:16.500
looking at because there's no way of evaluating that information.

01:20:16.840 --> 01:20:18.320
You don't rule it out.

01:20:18.700 --> 01:20:21.740
And we say, maybe there's something there, but...

01:20:21.740 --> 01:20:25.280
But then you become the cat that doesn't want, that cannot learn French.

01:20:25.740 --> 01:20:26.060
Maybe.

01:20:27.140 --> 01:20:31.080
No, no, I'm saying, look, this is a fascinating thing about the scientific method.

01:20:31.080 --> 01:20:36.940
We assume it's the end all, but clearly it isn't because it fails us over and over again.

01:20:37.360 --> 01:20:43.680
And so I went to a 100th reunion of my PhD program at Indiana University, you know, where

01:20:43.680 --> 01:20:45.660
B.F. Skinner was there, you know, these luminaries.

01:20:46.340 --> 01:20:51.440
And I was in industry, and I said, you know, I've been out 10 years, and I think the scientific

01:20:51.440 --> 01:20:53.580
method is really flawed and limited.

01:20:54.260 --> 01:20:55.240
And they said, why?

01:20:55.240 --> 01:21:01.540
And I said, because in science, you have to narrow things down so tiny and so narrow

01:21:01.540 --> 01:21:03.600
to reach a real robust conclusion.

01:21:04.160 --> 01:21:09.520
You have to control so much that it becomes inapplicable to the real world where nothing

01:21:09.520 --> 01:21:10.180
is controlled.

01:21:11.000 --> 01:21:14.600
And I said, in my world, where I'm in the fighter simulation business, and I have to

01:21:14.600 --> 01:21:19.920
figure out how to make a pilot think he's flying at 20 feet off the ground with very

01:21:19.920 --> 01:21:22.320
limited cues, there's no science for that.

01:21:22.520 --> 01:21:24.960
I just have to try a bunch of shit and see what works.

01:21:24.960 --> 01:21:29.940
And I said, I think the method is seriously flawed and limited.

01:21:30.280 --> 01:21:31.160
Oh, my God.

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:34.100
So I think that I will give you this.

01:21:34.360 --> 01:21:36.840
The scientific method itself is limited.

01:21:37.160 --> 01:21:37.480
Agree.

01:21:37.740 --> 01:21:42.860
It's the same thing as, you know, when you're looking for a body that's buried, maybe that

01:21:42.860 --> 01:21:47.000
person has an extra sense of smell that could smell what it is.

01:21:47.240 --> 01:21:52.980
Maybe that person has an extra sense of something that we don't know, we don't acknowledge that

01:21:52.980 --> 01:21:55.860
exists, and we don't have the tools to evaluate.

01:21:56.040 --> 01:22:03.780
So I think it is very possible that that particular person has a capability, capacity of finding

01:22:03.780 --> 01:22:04.320
a body somewhere.

01:22:04.320 --> 01:22:04.740
That's right.

01:22:04.960 --> 01:22:05.520
Like Joy Milne.

01:22:05.520 --> 01:22:10.840
And we don't know how to evaluate that possible capability.

01:22:11.280 --> 01:22:12.740
So I do agree.

01:22:12.820 --> 01:22:19.220
I think it's something we don't know, and we have no idea, and we should be open in discovery.

01:22:19.220 --> 01:22:20.400
I'll give you both a big yo.

01:22:20.900 --> 01:22:21.820
I like it.

01:22:21.880 --> 01:22:22.420
I like it.

01:22:22.420 --> 01:22:27.520
Yeah, it is one of those things where it's a paradigm-shifting thing, if real, and then

01:22:27.520 --> 01:22:28.320
we don't know if it's real.

01:22:28.420 --> 01:22:32.860
But you have this woman, Jessica Utz, who is president of the American Statistical Association.

01:22:32.860 --> 01:22:38.220
She looked at all the CIA data around Stargate, did a meta-study, and she came out saying if

01:22:38.220 --> 01:22:43.260
this were any other field and not parapsychology, which has this inherent kind of stigma stench

01:22:43.260 --> 01:22:47.840
attached to it, it would be beyond a shadow of doubt with the p-values she was looking at

01:22:47.840 --> 01:22:49.960
that this is totally real.

01:22:50.500 --> 01:22:55.820
And then, to me, it's like, okay, it's like black body radiation in the late 19th century

01:22:55.820 --> 01:23:00.600
where you can say it's fake because of the prevailing theory at the time, or let's try

01:23:00.600 --> 01:23:01.400
to find a theory.

01:23:02.220 --> 01:23:03.460
And I don't know, but...

01:23:03.460 --> 01:23:04.580
But like I say, maybe.

01:23:04.820 --> 01:23:05.320
Yeah, maybe.

01:23:05.520 --> 01:23:06.060
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:23:06.560 --> 01:23:11.720
But you see, the thing is, one reason you'll find me to be such a stickler is I kind of

01:23:11.720 --> 01:23:17.820
have to be to have credibility because I want hardcore scientists to look at the

01:23:17.820 --> 01:23:22.000
someone like me and someone like Dr. Gilbert and say they're not wild-eyed crazies.

01:23:22.120 --> 01:23:22.880
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:23:22.880 --> 01:23:24.560
They are disciplined.

01:23:24.740 --> 01:23:25.060
Sure.

01:23:25.760 --> 01:23:33.820
And so I'm purposely that way, you know, that I want to maintain healthy skepticism at the

01:23:33.820 --> 01:23:40.900
same time, oh, because the very best scientists realize that we're much more limited than we

01:23:40.900 --> 01:23:41.560
want to admit.

01:23:41.560 --> 01:23:47.580
And so what I want to do is speak to those scientists and say, play in this space because

01:23:47.580 --> 01:23:49.120
there's some exciting stuff here.

01:23:49.240 --> 01:23:52.480
I have no idea what it is, but I know what it isn't.

01:23:52.620 --> 01:23:54.860
And what it isn't is something we understand.

01:23:55.320 --> 01:23:55.980
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:23:56.480 --> 01:24:04.100
Was there any, while you were at NSA or ODNI, anything that's now declassified around the

01:24:04.100 --> 01:24:05.900
UFO stuff that came across your desk?

01:24:05.980 --> 01:24:07.560
Any signals intelligence or...

01:24:07.560 --> 01:24:12.540
No, and I'll tell you that inside the highest levels of the intelligence community, this

01:24:12.540 --> 01:24:15.400
is not something we spent a femto second thinking about.

01:24:15.480 --> 01:24:15.940
Any time.

01:24:15.980 --> 01:24:17.740
I don't think there was any point.

01:24:18.440 --> 01:24:24.980
I did get involved in some FOIA requests at NSA as a senior executive, but none of us

01:24:24.980 --> 01:24:26.820
spent any time on this.

01:24:27.080 --> 01:24:31.860
There's one guy I interviewed whose name is Dan Sherman, and he said he was taken to an

01:24:31.860 --> 01:24:39.840
NSA complex, and he was, like, kind of humming these, like, tones with his headphones, and

01:24:39.840 --> 01:24:45.280
then it was, that was all meant to, so he could communicate with non-human intelligence.

01:24:45.280 --> 01:24:51.440
And he said, I'm going to play a tone, and I want you to mentally hum that tone.

01:24:51.440 --> 01:24:57.600
And he said that you will eventually feel a connection, the line will change.

01:24:58.080 --> 01:25:03.660
When I saw the sine wave move, I went, oh, okay.

01:25:04.080 --> 01:25:05.780
Oh, I heard about something like that, yeah.

01:25:05.780 --> 01:25:07.560
It's called Above Black is the book he wrote.

01:25:07.700 --> 01:25:07.840
Yeah.

01:25:07.840 --> 01:25:09.160
Project Preserve Destiny.

01:25:09.320 --> 01:25:10.380
Do you have a take on that?

01:25:10.380 --> 01:25:11.040
No, no.

01:25:11.040 --> 01:25:11.200
Okay.

01:25:11.200 --> 01:25:18.740
I heard about it, but I will tell you that, look, at that level, you're interested in budgets,

01:25:18.740 --> 01:25:26.380
policy, and I'm trying to get more money to do high-risk, high-reward research in the

01:25:26.380 --> 01:25:26.800
community.

01:25:26.960 --> 01:25:32.760
That consumed 100% of my time, and I, except when I was going to be interviewed by 60 Minutes,

01:25:32.780 --> 01:25:35.800
and they wanted to ask me about this, it never even came up.

01:25:35.800 --> 01:25:36.400
Mm-hmm.

01:25:36.620 --> 01:25:43.120
In thinking about kind of terrestrial propulsion modalities that could explain what we're seeing,

01:25:43.200 --> 01:25:48.340
because this is part of your book, is there anything you guys are aware of or think could

01:25:48.340 --> 01:25:51.840
be possible that transcends chemical combustion?

01:25:52.120 --> 01:25:52.420
Yes.

01:25:52.640 --> 01:25:52.940
Okay.

01:25:53.260 --> 01:25:53.580
Yes.

01:25:54.100 --> 01:26:01.300
I'm glad you brought that up, because we go through NASA's innovative propulsion program,

01:26:01.480 --> 01:26:04.520
which I think is fantastic, because it's one part of the government that's saying,

01:26:04.520 --> 01:26:07.700
we will fund anything that isn't impossible.

01:26:08.800 --> 01:26:10.320
I love that approach.

01:26:10.800 --> 01:26:13.380
And they give you a little funding if you can play with it.

01:26:13.440 --> 01:26:15.180
And an example of that is a warp drive.

01:26:15.180 --> 01:26:16.020
Mm-hmm.

01:26:16.660 --> 01:26:22.140
And again, in our book, The Shadow of Time, we get into the possibilities of, you know,

01:26:22.460 --> 01:26:27.040
what people don't talk about when you talk about traveling near the speed of light is

01:26:27.040 --> 01:26:29.260
the acceleration and deceleration.

01:26:29.760 --> 01:26:30.100
Mm-hmm.

01:26:30.180 --> 01:26:30.380
Right?

01:26:30.500 --> 01:26:34.540
You've got to accelerate from nothing to near the speed of light, and then you've got to

01:26:34.540 --> 01:26:36.120
slow down to get where you're going to go.

01:26:36.220 --> 01:26:36.380
Huh.

01:26:36.380 --> 01:26:43.160
Well, either those take a really long time, which gets rid of a lot of the advantage of

01:26:43.160 --> 01:26:49.880
traveling that fast, or you have an organism that can withstand unbelievable Gs, which...

01:26:49.880 --> 01:26:50.160
Yeah.

01:26:50.160 --> 01:26:51.540
Yeah, we studied.

01:26:51.740 --> 01:26:54.380
There were some studies done on that.

01:26:54.860 --> 01:27:02.700
Because for organisms to be able to travel from outer space to Earth, for example,

01:27:03.240 --> 01:27:10.480
they need to be able to resist extreme cold, extreme heat, extremely long journeys,

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:17.200
so extreme accelerations, extreme decelerations, and intense radiation, cosmic radiation.

01:27:17.200 --> 01:27:19.080
So is it possible?

01:27:19.440 --> 01:27:22.400
Has there been anything like this?

01:27:22.480 --> 01:27:23.540
Well, there has been.

01:27:24.760 --> 01:27:34.700
So we've done studies on, like, for example, when we're talking about nuclear plants.

01:27:35.080 --> 01:27:43.400
So there is an organism, a bacterium called Deinococcus radiodurans, which can resist intense

01:27:43.400 --> 01:27:44.000
radiation.

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:46.580
It can actually thrive on intense radiation.

01:27:46.580 --> 01:27:52.700
But also it can survive cold, dehydration, vacuum, and acid.

01:27:53.200 --> 01:27:55.340
So it's an extremophile.

01:27:55.600 --> 01:27:58.380
And we've got a few that are extremophiles.

01:27:58.540 --> 01:28:05.460
And this one, the Deinococcus radiodurans, has been found to survive three years in outer

01:28:05.460 --> 01:28:10.820
space based on the studies conducted on the International Space Station.

01:28:11.800 --> 01:28:13.500
Now, we've done studies on ants.

01:28:13.500 --> 01:28:20.920
There are certain types of ants that can sustain 5,000 Gs, so 5,000 times the force of gravity.

01:28:21.160 --> 01:28:21.260
Wow.

01:28:22.260 --> 01:28:23.320
There are tardigrades.

01:28:23.440 --> 01:28:24.260
What are tardigrades?

01:28:24.380 --> 01:28:29.740
There are little bears that are from half a millimeter to 1.2 millimeters.

01:28:30.120 --> 01:28:31.480
They have eight legs.

01:28:31.480 --> 01:28:35.600
And they're found on moss or fresh or seawater sediment.

01:28:35.600 --> 01:28:43.440
And they can sustain 16,000 Gs, like 16,000 times the force of gravity, when a human will

01:28:43.440 --> 01:28:47.420
be killed with a sustained exposure to 12 Gs.

01:28:47.420 --> 01:28:55.800
So, and those little tardigrades can survive 30 years at zero degree Fahrenheit, can survive

01:28:55.800 --> 01:28:58.260
10 years in a dehydrated state.

01:28:58.880 --> 01:29:05.220
And NASA did an experiment where they survived 18 months in the vacuum of space, same thing

01:29:05.220 --> 01:29:07.520
outside the International Space Station.

01:29:07.520 --> 01:29:09.220
Now, there are fruit flies.

01:29:09.640 --> 01:29:18.940
Fruit flies, surprisingly, those little teeny things are able to withstand up to 17,000 Gs,

01:29:18.980 --> 01:29:22.380
17,000 times the force of gravity.

01:29:22.860 --> 01:29:24.260
There are roundworms.

01:29:25.260 --> 01:29:26.660
Roundworms, they're parasite.

01:29:26.860 --> 01:29:29.500
They can be parasite in animals or also in humans.

01:29:29.500 --> 01:29:33.920
They can withstand 80,000 Gs.

01:29:35.060 --> 01:29:43.880
And in 2023, it was reported that an individual nematode has been revived after 46,000 years

01:29:43.880 --> 01:29:46.480
in the Siberian permafrost.

01:29:47.580 --> 01:29:55.080
And talking about organisms that are resistant to extreme conditions, like in the bottom of

01:29:55.080 --> 01:30:01.900
the ocean, near the bottom of the ocean, at five miles below the ocean, which is 26,000

01:30:01.900 --> 01:30:10.700
feet below the surface, near hydrothermal vents, there are cells that can survive.

01:30:10.840 --> 01:30:17.040
There is an ocean worm that the home is located near hydrothermal vents.

01:30:17.200 --> 01:30:19.320
And it's not crushed.

01:30:19.320 --> 01:30:26.880
There's a Mariana snailfish that can live near the Mariana or in the Mariana Trench in the

01:30:26.880 --> 01:30:27.960
Western Pacific Ocean.

01:30:27.960 --> 01:30:37.300
So imagine an organism that is under five miles of water, that heavy, heavy weight that would

01:30:37.300 --> 01:30:40.260
crush any kind of organism, would crush us.

01:30:40.460 --> 01:30:44.240
And it does not crush a snailfish.

01:30:44.620 --> 01:30:47.040
It doesn't crush a little worm.

01:30:47.720 --> 01:30:48.600
Why is that?

01:30:48.600 --> 01:30:49.960
How is that, you know?

01:30:50.420 --> 01:30:54.620
So I think the bottom line of everything that she's saying is we should never say never when

01:30:54.620 --> 01:31:00.060
it comes to nothing can sustain interstellar travel, nothing can sustain the kind of Gs

01:31:00.060 --> 01:31:04.580
that we see with the tic-tac, that we actually have existence proofs that those things are

01:31:04.580 --> 01:31:05.040
possible.

01:31:05.280 --> 01:31:10.040
But getting back to the question you asked about propulsion, which this is relevant because

01:31:10.040 --> 01:31:14.140
some of these propulsions get to extreme accelerations and radiation even.

01:31:14.140 --> 01:31:21.380
Um, the ones that I think are the most interesting are where you're not putting the power source

01:31:21.380 --> 01:31:22.700
on the vehicle.

01:31:23.100 --> 01:31:29.140
So for example, um, we have this video and we know the guy who did it at Sandia National

01:31:29.140 --> 01:31:35.420
Lab and at White Sands where you take a disc, a flying saucer basically, and you put a pulse

01:31:35.420 --> 01:31:39.800
laser, just like I said, and you shoot it up and you propel it with laser energy.

01:31:40.040 --> 01:31:40.180
Whoa.

01:31:40.560 --> 01:31:40.720
Right.

01:31:40.720 --> 01:31:43.980
So you can move something through the air where there's no engine on it at all.

01:31:44.060 --> 01:31:45.480
You're just pushing on it with photons.

01:31:45.660 --> 01:31:46.860
Did you do that at a larger scale?

01:31:47.020 --> 01:31:47.300
Yes.

01:31:47.480 --> 01:31:47.840
Whoa.

01:31:47.980 --> 01:31:54.120
In fact, this guy that, uh, we've talked to did it for the government and he's been forever

01:31:54.120 --> 01:31:56.380
trying to say, look, you want clean energy?

01:31:56.820 --> 01:31:58.400
You don't need any fuel at all.

01:31:58.460 --> 01:32:01.100
You just use a laser beam or a microwave to push it.

01:32:01.220 --> 01:32:02.820
What's the, can you say the guy's name or?

01:32:03.060 --> 01:32:05.420
Um, I'd have to look it up.

01:32:05.620 --> 01:32:09.680
Um, he, uh, and I don't know he'd want himself.

01:32:09.680 --> 01:32:14.880
He's a little private, but, but, uh, you can go online and you can look at, uh, laser

01:32:14.880 --> 01:32:20.380
propelled disc and you can see a video and it looks exactly like a flying saucer just

01:32:20.380 --> 01:32:21.440
levitating up.

01:32:22.080 --> 01:32:24.000
Are we investing heavily in this?

01:32:24.060 --> 01:32:24.900
If you can do that at high.

01:32:25.080 --> 01:32:25.280
No.

