Okay.

01:32:25.800 --> 01:32:28.940
Well, this gets into another thing and this is his frustration.

01:32:29.200 --> 01:32:29.400
Yeah.

01:32:29.520 --> 01:32:29.640
Yeah.

01:32:29.880 --> 01:32:36.200
Um, is that if this were successful, it would threaten a huge established, you know, jet

01:32:36.200 --> 01:32:39.660
engine and, uh, and, uh, he, he wants to use it.

01:32:39.680 --> 01:32:40.600
For civil aviation.

01:32:41.240 --> 01:32:41.640
Right.

01:32:42.140 --> 01:32:45.660
And he's done the math and now with adaptive optics at the time he first doing this, you

01:32:45.660 --> 01:32:47.060
could only do it at short distances.

01:32:47.380 --> 01:32:47.520
Yeah.

01:32:47.600 --> 01:32:53.440
But we have adaptive optics now where we can control for atmospheric losses and distortion

01:32:53.440 --> 01:32:54.980
of the beam and stuff like that.

01:32:55.540 --> 01:33:00.640
And, uh, I think when it comes to getting things into low earth orbit in particular, this ought

01:33:00.640 --> 01:33:01.520
to really be looked at.

01:33:01.640 --> 01:33:01.840
Yeah.

01:33:01.840 --> 01:33:08.340
But, but, but in NASA's program, they look at a lot of things from, uh, laser propulsion

01:33:08.340 --> 01:33:16.480
in space, light sails, and they also look at, uh, fusion reactors where you basically create

01:33:16.480 --> 01:33:20.680
a fusion reaction and you spew gamma rays out the back.

01:33:20.680 --> 01:33:25.360
And again, it's photon pressure, you know, a photon doesn't have any mass, but it has

01:33:25.360 --> 01:33:25.860
momentum.

01:33:26.320 --> 01:33:30.960
So when a photon hits something, it imparts its momentum to it and it will move it.

01:33:31.200 --> 01:33:31.640
Right.

01:33:31.880 --> 01:33:38.360
And, um, so, uh, I think that to me, those are some of the more interesting, but there

01:33:38.360 --> 01:33:42.280
are some other really weird ones like magnetic levitation.

01:33:42.660 --> 01:33:43.100
Right.

01:33:43.100 --> 01:33:48.420
For example, did you know it's possible for me to levitate you with a super strong magnet?

01:33:49.080 --> 01:33:49.520
Levitate me?

01:33:49.700 --> 01:33:49.840
Yeah.

01:33:49.980 --> 01:33:50.520
No, I didn't do that.

01:33:50.520 --> 01:33:52.840
But we've done it with birds and frogs and spiders.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:53.320
What?

01:33:53.580 --> 01:33:53.780
Yeah.

01:33:54.000 --> 01:33:55.460
And, uh, here's the way it works.

01:33:56.380 --> 01:34:05.260
Magnetism isn't just what you think of as a, uh, uh, like a piece of iron or a rare earth

01:34:05.260 --> 01:34:06.340
magnet or something like that.

01:34:06.360 --> 01:34:07.740
It's what we call ferromagnetism.

01:34:08.340 --> 01:34:10.260
There are a zillion other kinds of magnetism.

01:34:10.460 --> 01:34:11.980
There's ferromagnetism.

01:34:11.980 --> 01:34:14.060
There's diamagnetism.

01:34:14.320 --> 01:34:15.780
There's paramagnetism.

01:34:16.060 --> 01:34:20.940
And these all have to do with, if you have a charged particle that's spinning, it will

01:34:20.940 --> 01:34:22.000
create a magnetic field.

01:34:22.720 --> 01:34:22.840
Okay.

01:34:22.960 --> 01:34:27.500
Sometimes that magnetic field works in the direction of the inducing magnetic field.

01:34:27.920 --> 01:34:30.180
Sometimes it's with diamagnetic, it's the opposite.

01:34:30.400 --> 01:34:33.800
So you get, you get, instead of things being attracted, they get pushed away.

01:34:34.060 --> 01:34:34.600
Like bismuth.

01:34:35.120 --> 01:34:35.480
Yes.

01:34:35.660 --> 01:34:35.900
Yeah.

01:34:36.020 --> 01:34:36.460
Exactly.

01:34:37.320 --> 01:34:37.800
Yes.

01:34:37.800 --> 01:34:40.400
And that was found maybe with a UFO and they think, man, maybe.

01:34:40.400 --> 01:34:42.840
So it could have magnetic levitation.

01:34:43.040 --> 01:34:43.240
Yeah.

01:34:43.380 --> 01:34:44.360
And that's possible.

01:34:44.360 --> 01:34:50.060
And you can take non-metallic things and you can tractor beam them basically.

01:34:50.420 --> 01:34:50.940
Right.

01:34:51.140 --> 01:34:53.660
There's also such a thing as optical tweezers.

01:34:53.900 --> 01:34:54.240
Wow.

01:34:54.240 --> 01:35:01.540
Where if you create a very, very strong electromagnetic field with a laser that's very precise, you

01:35:01.540 --> 01:35:07.220
can move particles of dust around with this laser and it's called an optical tweezer.

01:35:07.460 --> 01:35:12.580
So remote force fields, if you will, are absolutely possible.

01:35:12.580 --> 01:35:20.540
Now, when you do the math of how big a magnetic field you would need to control something many

01:35:20.540 --> 01:35:25.220
miles away, it gets to be, but I wouldn't say it's impossible.

01:35:25.220 --> 01:35:30.900
What I'm saying is magnetic fields decrease as the cube of the distance as you go away.

01:35:31.020 --> 01:35:32.800
It's not inverse square, it's inverse cubed.

01:35:33.100 --> 01:35:36.320
Because they're dipoles, there's no such thing as a magnetic monopole.

01:35:36.320 --> 01:35:41.180
So at the same time you have one magnetic field reinforcing, you have the opposite end

01:35:41.180 --> 01:35:41.880
taking away.

01:35:42.100 --> 01:35:44.920
So this is in Maxwell's equations, right?

01:35:45.040 --> 01:35:49.980
So essentially to a first order goes off as a cube.

01:35:50.480 --> 01:35:57.720
So to have a steep magnetic gradient that would cause this at a very long distance, we have

01:35:57.720 --> 01:35:59.960
no idea how to do that, but we can't say it's impossible.

01:35:59.960 --> 01:36:05.240
So pushing and pulling with magnetic fields is possible.

01:36:06.000 --> 01:36:08.540
These fusion drives are kind of interesting.

01:36:09.320 --> 01:36:14.580
And the most interesting of all is the warp drive.

01:36:15.380 --> 01:36:15.460
Okay.

01:36:15.860 --> 01:36:20.160
So now this is when you get into, NASA has funded this.

01:36:20.320 --> 01:36:21.040
Okay.

01:36:21.240 --> 01:36:24.700
Even though they don't know that it's possible, they don't know that it's impossible.

01:36:25.020 --> 01:36:25.320
Okay.

01:36:25.320 --> 01:36:30.880
Some physicists have postulated what they call negative energy, which isn't the same

01:36:30.880 --> 01:36:35.260
as the energy we see, you know, black, dark energy.

01:36:35.440 --> 01:36:36.740
It's not the same as dark energy.

01:36:37.700 --> 01:36:42.700
Negative energy, because energy and mass are basically the same thing.

01:36:42.840 --> 01:36:43.020
Yeah.

01:36:43.160 --> 01:36:45.280
They create gravitational effects.

01:36:45.900 --> 01:36:51.820
So pure energy has a gravitational effect and so forth, slows down space-time, all that.

01:36:51.820 --> 01:36:57.400
But what happens with this energy is that it creates a repulsion.

01:36:57.840 --> 01:37:07.180
So the Albuquerque drive, right, is basically you have a huge mass or energy in front, which

01:37:07.180 --> 01:37:11.520
is positive mass or energy, and you have a huge negative in back.

01:37:11.680 --> 01:37:14.640
And so you create a wave of space-time that's moved.

01:37:14.640 --> 01:37:20.800
So the way the warp drive works is imagine a surfer who's on a wave and is stationary with

01:37:20.800 --> 01:37:23.060
respect to the wave, but the wave is moving.

01:37:23.400 --> 01:37:27.620
And we know that space-time can move at faster than the speed of light.

01:37:27.720 --> 01:37:27.900
Yeah.

01:37:28.100 --> 01:37:33.780
Because the hyperinflation that happened after the Big Bang, or some think that happened,

01:37:34.300 --> 01:37:39.800
which is a pretty good evidence for it, is that space-time itself can move faster than

01:37:39.800 --> 01:37:40.380
the speed of light.

01:37:40.380 --> 01:37:44.740
Which means that if you're in a bubble of space-time that's moving faster than the speed

01:37:44.740 --> 01:37:49.000
of light, you're not going to experience any acceleration or deceleration because you're

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:50.280
not moving in that frame.

01:37:50.840 --> 01:37:50.940
Yeah.

01:37:51.240 --> 01:37:53.940
Seems like a really hard engineering problem.

01:37:54.340 --> 01:37:55.160
Oh, yeah.

01:37:55.420 --> 01:37:57.760
Well, first of all, we don't know that negative energy exists.

01:37:57.860 --> 01:38:00.580
It's the same kind of thing that would have to keep a wormhole open.

01:38:00.800 --> 01:38:01.160
Yeah, right.

01:38:01.360 --> 01:38:01.540
Right.

01:38:01.680 --> 01:38:07.160
The only way a wormhole works is if you have that in the middle to keep things from collapsing.

01:38:07.160 --> 01:38:12.620
But it is interesting because Miguel Alcubierre did this proof that theoretically, even within

01:38:12.620 --> 01:38:17.060
general relativity, you could get faster than light travel if you do have negative energy.

01:38:17.800 --> 01:38:18.240
And so...

01:38:18.240 --> 01:38:18.640
Yeah, yeah.

01:38:18.660 --> 01:38:24.420
So again, and in our book, The Shadow of Time, we explore this as a kind of a plot point,

01:38:24.780 --> 01:38:25.140
you know.

01:38:25.540 --> 01:38:30.460
And so that's the kind of thing that I find kind of exciting.

01:38:30.780 --> 01:38:32.840
And here's kind of what I think is going to happen.

01:38:33.380 --> 01:38:36.300
Someone's going to keep looking at that, and they won't find that.

01:38:36.300 --> 01:38:36.740
Mm-hmm.

01:38:36.740 --> 01:38:41.060
That'll turn out not to be possible or not to be true, but they'll discover something else.

01:38:41.580 --> 01:38:42.380
Yeah, exactly.

01:38:42.760 --> 01:38:47.400
And this is why the study of UFOs is so important.

01:38:47.660 --> 01:38:48.040
Yes.

01:38:48.180 --> 01:38:50.500
You know, if we don't make any other point, I want to make this point.

01:38:50.920 --> 01:38:56.720
That in all of science, the biggest discoveries are by definition those we don't expect.

01:38:56.840 --> 01:38:57.600
And why is that?

01:38:58.160 --> 01:39:03.380
You know, if I ask you to imagine a color you've never seen before, it's really hard to do.

01:39:03.580 --> 01:39:03.780
Yeah.

01:39:03.780 --> 01:39:04.300
Right?

01:39:04.480 --> 01:39:06.540
But if you saw it, you could recognize it.

01:39:06.640 --> 01:39:06.920
Mm-hmm.

01:39:07.260 --> 01:39:12.240
And because when we imagine something, we have to do it from the building blocks of our experience.

01:39:12.380 --> 01:39:12.500
Yeah.

01:39:12.540 --> 01:39:14.800
If we have no experience, we can't imagine it.

01:39:15.020 --> 01:39:21.140
But if we put ourself in a position to observe something new, we may see something we could

01:39:21.140 --> 01:39:22.020
never have imagined.

01:39:22.340 --> 01:39:25.280
And that's where the biggest breakthroughs almost always come from.

01:39:25.280 --> 01:39:31.980
I set out to do A. I looked while I was doing it in my peripheral vision, and I saw B, and

01:39:31.980 --> 01:39:33.420
I go, ooh, that's more interesting.

01:39:33.640 --> 01:39:33.820
Yeah.

01:39:34.100 --> 01:39:38.960
And I think the reason for people to really get serious about studying what's going on

01:39:38.960 --> 01:39:41.460
here is we're going to see B, C, D, and E.

01:39:41.740 --> 01:39:42.020
Mm.

01:39:42.420 --> 01:39:45.560
We shoot for the stars, you land on the moon, and the moon's pretty cool.

01:39:45.560 --> 01:39:47.180
You land somewhere unexpected.

01:39:47.540 --> 01:39:48.100
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:39:48.100 --> 01:39:53.100
And again, remember, that's where discovery has to happen, where by definition, you can't

01:39:53.100 --> 01:39:53.680
imagine it.

01:39:53.840 --> 01:39:54.120
Yes.

01:39:54.560 --> 01:40:00.560
Yeah, I love the Henri Bergson quote, which is, the eyes can only see what the mind can

01:40:00.560 --> 01:40:00.980
comprehend.

01:40:01.360 --> 01:40:04.900
And you need a hypothesis in order to see something to begin with.

01:40:04.980 --> 01:40:10.740
And so I think that's probably actually the most underrated aspect of the phenomena is

01:40:10.740 --> 01:40:17.120
that our vision is, I mean, this is kind of an iconized virtual reality interface.

01:40:17.120 --> 01:40:24.340
And we superimpose our, we have like a meme library in our heads, and we superimpose these

01:40:24.340 --> 01:40:26.940
pre-existing building blocks onto the thing.

01:40:27.080 --> 01:40:33.140
And so in the 1890s, people would see airships, which were like on the edge of what was even

01:40:33.140 --> 01:40:33.980
possible at the time.

01:40:34.060 --> 01:40:35.440
You had like Zeppelins and stuff.

01:40:35.580 --> 01:40:39.800
And now we're seeing these like faster than light, you know, saucers and that sort of thing.

01:40:39.800 --> 01:40:46.920
So it's, there's something going on where we are using what's available to us and superimposing

01:40:46.920 --> 01:40:47.680
it, I think.

01:40:48.100 --> 01:40:48.660
That's right.

01:40:49.020 --> 01:40:52.380
And that's why AI is so important.

01:40:52.380 --> 01:40:58.340
But I'm not worried about AI supplanting or being there instead of our brain.

01:40:58.700 --> 01:41:04.440
I think AI will always be important in the future in addition to our brain, because it

01:41:04.440 --> 01:41:12.220
can only work together, because the AI will not be trained on anything else that it doesn't

01:41:12.220 --> 01:41:12.540
know.

01:41:12.680 --> 01:41:17.760
But the brain will be able to detect something that is different and will be able to train

01:41:17.760 --> 01:41:18.320
the AI.

01:41:18.320 --> 01:41:25.560
So it will always have to be an augmented brain that will be allowed with the AI.

01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:28.740
But I think the, our brain will always be necessary.

01:41:29.220 --> 01:41:30.240
We should not rely.

01:41:30.240 --> 01:41:30.660
Well, yours will.

01:41:30.720 --> 01:41:31.480
I don't know about mine.

01:41:31.820 --> 01:41:39.260
We should never rely on AI, solely AI, because people never see anything else.

01:41:39.280 --> 01:41:44.520
I think there's something very powerful though, in what she said, if you extend it and take

01:41:44.520 --> 01:41:46.600
into account what I said about the negative space.

01:41:46.600 --> 01:41:54.940
We should train up an AI that is the opposite of us in every way, not like us, but the opposite

01:41:54.940 --> 01:41:57.380
of us, and ask it to look at these questions.

01:41:58.060 --> 01:41:59.460
That's a great, yeah, I love that.

01:41:59.460 --> 01:42:00.820
We need an anti-AI.

01:42:01.180 --> 01:42:01.800
Yeah, right.

01:42:01.980 --> 01:42:02.180
Right?

01:42:02.320 --> 01:42:04.220
Train it on everything that isn't.

01:42:04.240 --> 01:42:05.160
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:42:05.280 --> 01:42:05.840
I love that.

01:42:05.960 --> 01:42:09.880
And see what it says, because, I mean, that's the clear implication of what she's saying,

01:42:09.880 --> 01:42:13.520
where, you know, an AI can just do what we do, only better.

01:42:13.980 --> 01:42:15.140
Okay, that's useful.

01:42:15.820 --> 01:42:20.900
But an AI that can do things we cannot do and would not ever do is the one that's really

01:42:20.900 --> 01:42:21.580
going to pay off.

01:42:21.740 --> 01:42:21.840
Yeah.

01:42:22.020 --> 01:42:23.640
The question is, would we ever believe it?

01:42:23.980 --> 01:42:24.660
Yeah, exactly.

01:42:24.840 --> 01:42:29.900
Well, that's the problem with LLMs is they kind of inherently triangulate actually the

01:42:29.900 --> 01:42:30.420
consensus.

01:42:30.420 --> 01:42:35.880
So they're going for, usually, the middle-of-the-road kind of most acceptable answer.

01:42:36.420 --> 01:42:42.160
And so if you could train a more kind of heretical thinking AI or something, you know, an AI on

01:42:42.160 --> 01:42:47.380
the bleeding edge of what's acceptable and maybe decamp it from the instinct that you

01:42:47.380 --> 01:42:52.120
were talking about, you know, even, I think, before we were filming, Eric, where people

01:42:52.120 --> 01:42:55.260
are socialized and ideas are fashion statements.

01:42:55.260 --> 01:42:58.900
And, you know, it's hard to truly think in a heterodox way.

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:01.360
If you could train an AI to do that, that would be amazing.

01:43:02.040 --> 01:43:02.220
Yeah.

01:43:02.280 --> 01:43:07.560
And that's why we need an increase in the research budget and not a decrease in research

01:43:07.560 --> 01:43:07.820
budget.

01:43:07.820 --> 01:43:08.140
Yeah.

01:43:08.140 --> 01:43:09.160
Don't get me started.

01:43:09.700 --> 01:43:10.600
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:43:10.960 --> 01:43:18.920
But I think research, all over the world, research is going to increase and a lot of governments

01:43:18.920 --> 01:43:21.320
are going to discover a lot of interesting things.

01:43:21.320 --> 01:43:28.840
Yeah, well, there's a great essay called The Usefulness of Useless Things.

01:43:29.060 --> 01:43:30.100
I don't know if you're familiar with it.

01:43:30.140 --> 01:43:33.760
It's by this guy, Abraham Flexner, and it was kind of the charter for the Institute of

01:43:33.760 --> 01:43:35.900
Advanced Study at Princeton back in the day.

01:43:36.120 --> 01:43:41.640
And it was all about, we should pour a ton of money into things that don't have immediate

01:43:41.640 --> 01:43:42.140
use.

01:43:42.540 --> 01:43:47.280
If you think about, you know, quantum theory, which is responsible for semiconductors and,

01:43:47.280 --> 01:43:52.180
you know, a third plus of our economy today, it was like people philosophize, you know,

01:43:52.180 --> 01:43:54.540
thinking about the kookiest, weirdest stuff.

01:43:54.760 --> 01:43:57.480
And then it turns into something that's super productive.

01:43:57.720 --> 01:43:59.780
And so I agree with you.

01:43:59.840 --> 01:44:04.120
I think the idea that, you know, we should only spend money on things that are super locally

01:44:04.120 --> 01:44:10.120
useful is not only counterproductive, not only myopic, but it's actually counterproductive

01:44:10.120 --> 01:44:12.880
from like even a GDP boosting perspective.

01:44:13.020 --> 01:44:14.380
Like it's dumb politics too.

01:44:14.380 --> 01:44:19.380
So, yep, yeah, that's what we love to do with Eric.

01:44:19.500 --> 01:44:24.780
We love looking at completely outside the box of the weirdest things that are happening

01:44:24.780 --> 01:44:30.260
because we think that in the weirdest things are the clue of the clues of the future.

01:44:30.460 --> 01:44:30.700
I agree.

01:44:30.900 --> 01:44:31.740
Asimov's that's funny.

01:44:31.860 --> 01:44:33.420
We're always interested in that's funny.

01:44:33.520 --> 01:44:39.060
But again, we're hardcore scientists, so our interest is there, but we try to be disciplined

01:44:39.060 --> 01:44:40.200
when we look at those things.

01:44:40.200 --> 01:44:45.120
And most of them, you know, are unlikely, but there are a few, and those are the ones

01:44:45.120 --> 01:44:46.000
that really excite us.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:49.360
Like those tic-tacs, there's something real going on there.

01:44:49.460 --> 01:44:56.100
I mean, there's just too many independent parallel sensors on that thing by people who

01:44:56.100 --> 01:44:58.080
didn't want to see it, but saw it anyhow.

01:44:58.080 --> 01:45:04.100
And so those in particular, and so that's why in our book, The Shadow of Time, the novel,

01:45:04.260 --> 01:45:09.260
that's why the tic-tacs show up because those in particular, we come up with a narrative

01:45:09.260 --> 01:45:10.860
of what could really be going on there.

01:45:11.140 --> 01:45:11.220
Yeah.

01:45:11.340 --> 01:45:17.680
Well, I can't wait to get to The Shadow of Time because in many ways it is the maybe best

01:45:17.680 --> 01:45:24.360
conclusion, but embodied in fiction of this survey level overview of what you guys talk

01:45:24.360 --> 01:45:26.000
about in the new science of UFOs.

01:45:26.000 --> 01:45:29.720
And so it's this really cool thing, but I wanted to talk real quick on the propulsion

01:45:29.720 --> 01:45:30.080
front.

01:45:30.760 --> 01:45:34.320
I'm particularly high conviction in this thing called the Bifield-Brown effect.

01:45:34.440 --> 01:45:35.460
Have you ever heard of that?

01:45:35.580 --> 01:45:36.080
Tell us more.

01:45:36.480 --> 01:45:42.080
So it's this idea that you take a capacitor and you have a negative electrode, a positive

01:45:42.080 --> 01:45:45.260
electrode, and you have a high K dielectric in the middle, which is, you know, the ability

01:45:45.260 --> 01:45:46.940
to store, you know, high electric fields.

01:45:46.940 --> 01:45:47.940
Love it when you talk dirty.

01:45:47.940 --> 01:45:55.980
And I think there's all this interesting, you know, data around this mid-century inventor

01:45:55.980 --> 01:46:01.380
Townsend Brown and his ability to transcend, you know, chemical combustion in this very

01:46:01.380 --> 01:46:05.980
cool way with these high voltage experiments that he was doing with this capacitor experiment,

01:46:06.200 --> 01:46:10.820
which to me would lead to stuff that leads us beyond SpaceX.

01:46:10.820 --> 01:46:15.380
And I'm just very passionate about the idea that I think SpaceX is just limited.

01:46:15.660 --> 01:46:21.560
You know, it takes, with chemical combustion, it's 80,000 years to the next habitable planet,

01:46:21.720 --> 01:46:22.620
Proxima Centauri.

01:46:22.700 --> 01:46:23.760
And that's unacceptable.

01:46:24.020 --> 01:46:26.960
And nuclear thermal propulsion maybe cuts that in half or something.

01:46:27.640 --> 01:46:29.640
And so you need something like this.

01:46:29.760 --> 01:46:32.060
And I think it's legit.

01:46:32.320 --> 01:46:34.120
So I don't know if you guys have a take there.

01:46:34.120 --> 01:46:36.140
Well, OK, I know how capacitors work.

01:46:36.240 --> 01:46:37.560
I know how dielectrics work.

01:46:38.380 --> 01:46:40.660
And so in what way could this be used for propulsion?

01:46:42.100 --> 01:46:47.180
So you get thrust from the negative electrode to the positive electrode.

01:46:47.580 --> 01:46:48.900
And you could do this.

01:46:49.020 --> 01:46:53.800
Apparently, you get more thrust, actually, in a vacuum than you do in air.

01:46:54.080 --> 01:46:59.760
And a lot of people try to explain it away because of the ionized air bombards.

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:01.860
You know, the ionized wind bombards the air.

01:47:01.860 --> 01:47:04.680
And then you get this equal and opposite reaction and you get thrust.

01:47:05.400 --> 01:47:07.720
But I think you see even more thrust in a vacuum.

01:47:07.900 --> 01:47:11.080
And so you could end up with all sorts of cool space propulsion modalities.

01:47:11.940 --> 01:47:13.160
And then, and then, yeah.

01:47:13.440 --> 01:47:15.620
Oh, there have been things like the EM drive.

01:47:15.760 --> 01:47:16.680
The EM drive, sure.

01:47:16.780 --> 01:47:17.040
Yeah.

01:47:17.240 --> 01:47:19.460
But the EM drive got debunked, I think, by.

01:47:19.560 --> 01:47:21.440
Yeah, it keeps getting debunked.

01:47:21.540 --> 01:47:25.460
But people keep throwing money at it anyhow.

01:47:26.720 --> 01:47:26.880
Yeah.

01:47:26.920 --> 01:47:29.460
And I think this thing you're talking about has that quality.

01:47:29.460 --> 01:47:32.680
Because conservation of energy says that can't happen.

01:47:33.120 --> 01:47:34.200
Or Newton's.

01:47:34.460 --> 01:47:34.820
Yes.

01:47:34.940 --> 01:47:39.180
Newton's law, where you have to have a reaction mass in order to get thrust.

01:47:39.400 --> 01:47:43.900
In other words, you have to throw mass or energy out the back in order to move in a particular direction.

01:47:44.080 --> 01:47:44.760
A hundred percent.

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:45.120
Yeah.

01:47:45.120 --> 01:47:58.640
And the reason I put it in the parapsychology, the thing we were talking about earlier, I put it in that camp of there's a lot of evidence that these high electric field strength differentials result in thrust.

01:47:58.720 --> 01:48:00.280
And then we just don't have good theory around it.

01:48:00.320 --> 01:48:03.420
Like maybe there's something quantum electrodynamics we don't understand.

01:48:03.420 --> 01:48:24.400
Well, there's something interesting where there's this effect where if you take two plates, kind of like a capacitor, and they're very, very flat and very, very close together, because of quantum field, you will get the plates moving with respect to each other a tiny amount.

01:48:24.400 --> 01:48:26.320
And this has been observed in the laboratory.

01:48:26.500 --> 01:48:27.420
Yeah, Casimir effect.

01:48:27.460 --> 01:48:28.720
The Casimir effect, exactly.

01:48:29.400 --> 01:48:31.520
But that only works in one direction.

01:48:31.840 --> 01:48:32.040
Yeah.

01:48:33.120 --> 01:48:45.220
But yeah, I mean, it's one of these weird quantum things that is moving in the direction you're saying, because, okay, the thing we're attracted to each other, but what was the force?

01:48:45.520 --> 01:48:46.720
It's a quantum field.

01:48:46.860 --> 01:48:51.540
And that starts to get outside of, you know, the quantum realm is so bizarre.

01:48:51.660 --> 01:48:52.320
It's so bizarre.

01:48:52.420 --> 01:48:52.820
Exactly.

01:48:52.820 --> 01:49:03.900
You have this guy, Sonny White, out here, who's at NASA Eagle Works, and he claims that he can power up 1.5 kilovolts microchip with the Casimir effect.

01:49:04.480 --> 01:49:05.300
And so it's bizarre.

01:49:05.660 --> 01:49:06.740
And he's published this.

01:49:06.820 --> 01:49:08.160
And so I think that's so cool.

01:49:08.340 --> 01:49:09.680
You know, I don't know if it's right, but.

01:49:10.100 --> 01:49:10.340
Yo.

01:49:10.740 --> 01:49:12.040
Yeah, yo, there you go.

01:49:12.520 --> 01:49:17.800
And then one other thing on the astrobiology front is you were mentioning tardigrades and all the extremophiles.

01:49:18.220 --> 01:49:21.840
Have you guys thought of fungi or mushrooms as candidates?

01:49:21.840 --> 01:49:24.980
You know, they've been found on the International Space Station.

01:49:25.920 --> 01:49:29.500
And Francis Crick, who, of course, discovered the double helical structure of DNA.

01:49:29.760 --> 01:49:34.060
And his whole thing was like, you know, the 100 million years on Earth for DNA synthesis was impossible.

01:49:34.280 --> 01:49:38.300
Nobody's ever replicated this primordial soup experiment to create it.

01:49:38.300 --> 01:49:45.740
And so maybe you would send fungi across long distances in some sort of spaceship or something.

01:49:45.840 --> 01:49:47.660
Maybe you'd feed it algae and CO2.

01:49:48.000 --> 01:49:50.720
And the thing I like about fungi, it's so interesting.

01:49:50.720 --> 01:49:59.460
If you were to think about like a Kardashev three or four scale civilization, you wouldn't create this kind of like biological meat suit.

01:49:59.720 --> 01:50:05.880
You know, you show up as this, you know, gangly, you know, you know, bipedal being, you know, in some other planet.

01:50:05.880 --> 01:50:07.980
And you're immediately treated as a foreign invader.

01:50:08.280 --> 01:50:12.080
You would send an extremophile, which is like a zip file of consciousness.

01:50:12.840 --> 01:50:15.920
Humans all have microbiomes, but we have mycobiomes as well.

01:50:16.000 --> 01:50:17.120
So it affects our thinking.

01:50:17.120 --> 01:50:26.120
And they're extremophiles that you have, you know, cordyceps mushrooms in the Amazon kind of co-opting the actions of bullet ants.

01:50:26.460 --> 01:50:28.780
And so there's something I think very interesting.

01:50:29.020 --> 01:50:35.240
And then human tissue is very susceptible to fungal disease because it's so similar.

01:50:35.640 --> 01:50:41.960
You know, we're actually more similar to fungi than we are to most other plants and animals phylogenetically.

01:50:41.960 --> 01:50:50.640
And so it's this really interesting thing of what you would send this thing off that would like merge with the host, you know, and then it would affect their consciousness.

01:50:51.460 --> 01:50:54.060
Well, if they came here, it would be a fun guy.

01:50:54.940 --> 01:50:55.900
There you go.

01:50:55.940 --> 01:50:57.220
He'd be a load of fun.

01:50:57.340 --> 01:50:58.000
Yeah, it would.

01:50:58.100 --> 01:50:58.560
Yeah, there you go.

01:50:58.560 --> 01:51:01.820
Yeah, I mean, but I want to follow that thread just a little bit.

01:51:01.880 --> 01:51:02.040
Yeah.

01:51:02.340 --> 01:51:09.500
And, you know, just as we should never say they would do it the way we do it, we have to say maybe they would.

01:51:09.500 --> 01:51:15.460
And when we see in space probes, we don't send intentionally organisms.

01:51:16.140 --> 01:51:18.800
We send automated probes.

01:51:18.980 --> 01:51:22.040
And now with our AI, you know what's going to happen.

01:51:22.320 --> 01:51:26.500
We're going to be sending AIs out there because we don't have to have a life support system.

01:51:26.560 --> 01:51:28.200
We don't have to worry about any of that.

01:51:28.320 --> 01:51:35.960
And as our AI gets better and better and better, I think because, you know, Elon Musk said, we're not going to Mars after all.

01:51:35.980 --> 01:51:36.380
Right.

01:51:36.380 --> 01:51:37.260
More or less.

01:51:37.560 --> 01:51:40.420
And I'm on the Explore Mars Foundation group.

01:51:40.580 --> 01:51:41.720
And that was big.

01:51:41.840 --> 01:51:44.000
That was depressing for us because we want to explore Mars.

01:51:44.160 --> 01:51:48.300
But the fact is, we don't know how to send a human to Mars and bring him back in good shape.

01:51:48.900 --> 01:51:52.680
Radiation, low Gs, and hazards on Mars and so forth.

01:51:53.200 --> 01:51:58.060
And so where all that takes you is the first thing you're going to do is not going to be biological.

01:51:58.280 --> 01:51:59.300
It's going to be AI.

01:51:59.300 --> 01:52:08.080
And so that tells us that if something has come here from another civilization, it's probably, not certainly, it's probably a machine.

01:52:08.660 --> 01:52:09.040
That's right.

01:52:09.300 --> 01:52:12.340
It's probably some sort of von Neumann replicator probe or something.

01:52:12.480 --> 01:52:12.820
Or something.

01:52:13.080 --> 01:52:18.920
And that doesn't mean it's not alive because now you're getting into what is life.

01:52:18.920 --> 01:52:23.820
You know, and could an AI in a machine be alive?

01:52:24.500 --> 01:52:27.100
And this gets into what is life.

01:52:27.220 --> 01:52:29.940
And the biologists I know say it's simple.

01:52:30.040 --> 01:52:31.920
If a ball rolls downhill, it's dead.

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:33.480
If it rolls uphill, it's alive.

01:52:34.480 --> 01:52:37.340
Meaning life is locally negentropic.

01:52:37.900 --> 01:52:40.000
It behaves, it rolls uphill.

01:52:40.340 --> 01:52:40.860
Right.

01:52:40.960 --> 01:52:42.060
I love that definition.

01:52:42.200 --> 01:52:42.700
That's interesting.

01:52:42.700 --> 01:52:50.880
Yeah, and so could you have an artificial machine that to all intents and purposes, you know, had maybe emotions, had feelings?

01:52:51.080 --> 01:52:51.480
Probably.

01:52:51.860 --> 01:52:52.080
Yeah.

01:52:52.120 --> 01:52:54.780
We kind of have an existence proof that it could be done with atoms.

01:52:55.000 --> 01:52:55.240
Yeah.

01:52:55.340 --> 01:52:55.880
It's us.

01:52:56.460 --> 01:52:58.540
So I think that—

01:52:58.540 --> 01:53:00.020
It's like Maxwell's demons.

01:53:00.520 --> 01:53:00.700
Yeah.

01:53:01.120 --> 01:53:02.380
Macroscopic Maxwell's demons.

01:53:02.680 --> 01:53:03.000
Yes.

01:53:03.460 --> 01:53:05.120
Oh, yeah, yeah, exactly.

01:53:05.620 --> 01:53:06.060
Negantropic.

01:53:06.120 --> 01:53:06.700
Oh, yeah.

01:53:06.920 --> 01:53:07.440
I mean—

01:53:07.440 --> 01:53:08.300
Entropy reducers.

01:53:08.720 --> 01:53:09.160
Exactly.

01:53:09.320 --> 01:53:10.220
Oh, yeah, exactly.

01:53:10.220 --> 01:53:17.800
So the point is that when you look at these Tic Tacs and you see them moving around, you say, well, no biological being could do that.

01:53:17.840 --> 01:53:18.760
Well, maybe that's true.

01:53:19.400 --> 01:53:20.740
Maybe it's not biological.

01:53:20.960 --> 01:53:24.420
Maybe it's hardened electronics of some kind or, you know, something.

01:53:25.200 --> 01:53:32.120
But to me, if we're being visited by a probe from another civilization, it's probably technology, not biology.

01:53:32.120 --> 01:53:40.860
Well, there's all this lore in UFO world that the crafts are alive, and that even David Fravor, Commander David Fravor, said the crafts seem to be like breathing or something.

01:53:41.040 --> 01:53:42.200
That's another possibility.

01:53:42.340 --> 01:53:42.480
Yeah.

01:53:42.720 --> 01:53:44.720
Like that movie Nope, which I loved.

01:53:44.840 --> 01:53:45.260
Oh, yeah.

01:53:45.380 --> 01:53:46.000
Jordan Peele.

01:53:46.220 --> 01:53:46.340
Yeah.

01:53:46.340 --> 01:53:47.520
Yeah, where it's a cloud.

01:53:48.720 --> 01:53:48.960
Yeah.

01:53:48.960 --> 01:53:50.580
And the cloud just doesn't move, and you go, hmm.

01:53:50.580 --> 01:53:57.320
But, yeah, or, you know, as she was saying, as Dr. Gilbert was saying, what if, this is worth thinking about.

01:53:58.400 --> 01:54:03.060
Dark matter is dark to us because it doesn't interact with us, except very weakly, right?

01:54:03.100 --> 01:54:04.100
Or maybe not at all.

01:54:05.280 --> 01:54:09.660
So here's a, flip it around, what do we look like to dark matter?

01:54:10.460 --> 01:54:11.520
We look dark.

01:54:11.880 --> 01:54:12.140
Right.

01:54:12.140 --> 01:54:16.220
If it doesn't interact with us, we don't interact with it.

01:54:16.620 --> 01:54:17.020
Yes.

01:54:17.100 --> 01:54:19.440
And so to it, we're dark matter.

01:54:19.720 --> 01:54:20.160
Yes.

01:54:20.600 --> 01:54:21.000
Yes.

01:54:21.060 --> 01:54:21.260
Right?

01:54:21.380 --> 01:54:22.300
And we're alive.

01:54:22.660 --> 01:54:23.100
Yes.

01:54:23.540 --> 01:54:25.600
So what's to say it can't be alive?

01:54:25.980 --> 01:54:26.420
Right.

01:54:27.320 --> 01:54:27.760
Totally.

01:54:28.120 --> 01:54:28.340
Right?

01:54:28.420 --> 01:54:31.540
And so there's an example of a mind-expanding idea.

01:54:31.680 --> 01:54:32.080
Yeah.

01:54:32.180 --> 01:54:35.900
That's like way outside what a normal human is going to think about.

01:54:35.900 --> 01:54:41.960
Or I sometimes think about the ideas that we live in a kind of a computational universe, like the Wheeler stuff.

01:54:41.960 --> 01:54:43.300
Yeah, some sort of simulation.

01:54:43.600 --> 01:54:52.640
And then you look at Fermat's theorem, which is the travel of light, and it looks algorithmically optimized for, you know, kind of shortest path between two observers.

01:54:52.920 --> 01:54:56.340
Well, yeah, but that's kind of the path of least resistance.

01:54:56.340 --> 01:55:10.520
And you see that is a fascinating subject of fractals and how the veins of a tree or capillaries in your body or filaments of megastructures in outer space all look the same, the highest level down to the lowest level.

01:55:10.520 --> 01:55:12.500
And it's the path of least resistance.

01:55:13.360 --> 01:55:23.780
That's why those structures exist, because if you're trying to move atoms of water from A to B in the most efficient path with the least energy, that is the path.

01:55:24.420 --> 01:55:37.520
But then, I don't know, you think of if I were simulating something, I would copy code chunks, and then you'd get Fibonacci sequences and golden ratios and some of these things that seem like consistent architectures.

01:55:37.520 --> 01:55:50.540
See, that is so fascinating, these mathematical things like Fibonacci and fractals and holography and things like that, where math isn't a property of the universe.

01:55:50.600 --> 01:55:52.220
It doesn't describe the universe.

01:55:52.560 --> 01:55:54.040
It is the universe.

01:55:54.140 --> 01:55:54.400
Right.

01:55:54.400 --> 01:55:59.920
I mean, but now you're getting into Wolfram philosophical kind of stuff, and that's above my pay grade.

01:56:00.200 --> 01:56:00.620
Me too.

01:56:01.480 --> 01:56:07.400
Well, I want to talk about this amazing book, The Shadow of Time, which you guys should all go out and get.

01:56:08.040 --> 01:56:12.000
It is just fascinating, and I don't want to spoil it for people.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:33.480
So I think high level, it talks about an object that should not be found in the desert, that is a total kind of anachronism and involves kind of seemingly like, you know, elements or things that like, you know, shouldn't exist on Earth and look more advanced than, you know, the carbon dating.

01:56:33.480 --> 01:56:45.740
And a very kind of doggedly persistent paleontologist who is kind of pursuing this stuff and finds himself, honestly, in like a mafia war or something.

01:56:45.960 --> 01:56:51.980
Like, it's this wild, wild west landscape of people fighting for this forbidden archaeology.

01:56:52.260 --> 01:56:58.240
And as somebody who's mired in the UFO world, I think there might be some truth in fiction here.

01:56:59.040 --> 01:57:01.080
Well, what was our motivation?

01:57:01.080 --> 01:57:04.040
I think that's very important for the readers to understand.

01:57:04.320 --> 01:57:14.360
We finished The New Science of UFOs, which was a kind of intellectual exercise in the art of the possible and not impossible.

01:57:15.360 --> 01:57:20.680
And what we wanted to do is basically tell that same story in a way that would be more accessible to people.

01:57:20.680 --> 01:57:37.180
And to tell it from the point of view of interesting people and characters who had problems in their lives and make the science part of the story so that it became clues.

01:57:37.180 --> 01:57:54.840
And so as scientists, we will tell you that there's nothing more exciting than embarking on a scientific journey of discovery, solving a mystery and peeling back the onion one layer at a time and seeing something new and unexpected beneath, which only takes you deeper and deeper and deeper.

01:57:54.840 --> 01:58:05.000
So in addition to exploring the science of UFOs, we wanted to give the readers the feeling of what it's like to go on a journey of scientific discovery.

01:58:05.000 --> 01:58:14.280
And so one thing that happens in this book, you might remember, especially at the end, is there's a bunch of twists and turns like switchbacks up Mount Everest, right?

01:58:14.320 --> 01:58:17.980
It's like it's kind of like a whiplash, like, oh, that's true.

01:58:18.040 --> 01:58:18.340
That's true.

01:58:18.340 --> 01:58:30.240
Well, in science, that's what really happens, where you dig deep and you get answers that you weren't looking for that lead you to questions you weren't going to ask.

01:58:30.240 --> 01:58:50.320
And so at the end, there's this kind of rapid fire series of reveals of deeper and deeper truths where what you thought just a week ago is now today's illusion and you turn one illusion into one fact until you finally get to something that's close to the truth.

01:58:50.440 --> 01:58:52.160
And that's what science is like.

01:58:52.440 --> 01:58:57.540
So we have a lot of twists and turns on purpose and all of those are science driven.

01:58:57.540 --> 01:59:10.820
So there's a pretty much most of the science that was in the new science of UFOs is in here, but it's used to tell a story about people who are trying to overcome obstacles and rise above themselves.

01:59:11.120 --> 01:59:11.600
Yeah.

01:59:11.740 --> 01:59:20.080
So we we wanted to put a lot of science in there, but we wanted it to be exciting and we wanted it to be a mystery.

01:59:20.080 --> 01:59:33.200
And we wanted to we wanted the reader to do the discovery themselves and to be that like to be completely caught in the actions and what's going to happen that was going to happen next.

01:59:33.260 --> 01:59:38.640
And this is all this is deep into the science that we have studied for the other book.

01:59:38.640 --> 01:59:51.420
Yeah. And there's a lot of biology in there, a lot of exobiology. There's a lot of neuroscience. Neuroscience is very important. I am a neuroscientist and I'm really interested in species that are radically different from us.

01:59:51.420 --> 02:00:06.180
Hmm. And I would commend to people to read this book called An Immense World by Ed Young, in which he describes what he calls the Umwelt, a worldview of these exotic creatures like fish that have electric fields and sense electric fields, snakes.

02:00:06.180 --> 02:00:30.220
I got my PhD on snakes, rattlesnakes and pythons that see infrared, they see in the dark, the mantis shrimp that see 12 different colors that we don't see, you know. And I've been especially interested in that phenomena of organisms whose worldview and way of thinking and neuroanatomy is so radically different from ours. They cannot be like us.

02:00:30.220 --> 02:00:45.680
Hmm. And so that's exploring the negative space of the human condition. So the main, I guess, villain, you want to call it in this story, not exactly a villain, but, uh, is about as opposite a human as you could get.

02:00:45.680 --> 02:01:06.680
Yeah. Right. I mean, in every way, this creature is, is about as different from us as you can get. And the interactions between these completely alien us and them kinds of organisms, um, uh, contrast creates conflict, which makes things interesting.

02:01:06.680 --> 02:01:07.680
Mm-hmm.

02:01:07.680 --> 02:01:27.620
When each discovers their own limitations when looking through the world through the other's eyes. And so, um, we, we spent a lot of time and there's a lot of hardcore neuroscience in the way this creature is defined. And in some of the other characters is there's a lot of, uh, the kind of animal dimension.

02:01:27.620 --> 02:01:42.180
I studied in my PhD work and later, a lot of animal, uh, intelligence. And my conclusion from studying animals is that they're way smarter than we think they are. They're just not smart in ways that we're smart.

02:01:42.900 --> 02:01:43.740
Mm-hmm.

02:01:43.740 --> 02:01:54.660
Right? And this is what Ed Young is saying in his book. And so, um, there are two creatures in this story. One is a genius parrot named Walter.

02:01:54.660 --> 02:01:55.260
That's right.

02:01:55.460 --> 02:01:57.200
Who is not a nice character.

02:01:57.620 --> 02:01:58.060
No.

02:01:58.280 --> 02:02:00.460
No. Kind of like Iago in Aladdin.

02:02:00.600 --> 02:02:00.900
Right.

02:02:00.900 --> 02:02:02.020
